# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: organoids
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] A specialized type of differentiation, known as terminal differentiation, is of importance in some tissues, including vertebrate nervous system, striated muscle, epidermis and gut.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] During terminal differentiation, a precursor cell formerly capable of cell division permanently leaves the cell cycle, dismantles the cell cycle machinery and often expresses a range of genes characteristic of the cell's final function (e.g. myosin and actin for a muscle cell).
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Differentiation may continue to occur after terminal differentiation if the capacity and functions of the cell undergo further changes.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Among dividing cells, there are multiple levels of cell potency, which is the cell's ability to differentiate into other cell types.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] A greater potency indicates a larger number of cell types that can be derived.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] A cell that can differentiate into all cell types, including the placental tissue, is known as *totipotent*.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In mammals, only the zygote and subsequent blastomeres are totipotent, while in plants, many differentiated cells can become totipotent with simple laboratory techniques.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] A cell that can differentiate into all cell types of the adult organism is known as *pluripotent*.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Such cells are called meristematic cells in higher plants and embryonic stem cells in animals, though some groups report the presence of adult pluripotent cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Virally induced expression of four transcription factors Oct4, Sox2, c-Myc, and Klf4 (Yamanaka factors) is sufficient to create pluripotent (iPS) cells from adult fibroblasts.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] A multipotent cell is one that can differentiate into multiple different, but closely related cell types.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Oligopotent cells are more restricted than multipotent, but can still differentiate into a few closely related cell types.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Finally, unipotent cells can differentiate into only one cell type, but are capable of self-renewal.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In cytopathology, the level of cellular differentiation is used as a measure of cancer progression.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] "Grade" is a marker of how differentiated a cell in a tumor is.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Three basic categories of cells make up the mammalian body: germ cells, somatic cells, and stem cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Each of the approximately 37.2 trillion (3.72×1013) cells in an adult human has its own copy or copies of the genome except certain cell types, such as red blood cells, that lack nuclei in their fully differentiated state.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Most cells are diploid; they have two copies of each chromosome.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Such cells, called somatic cells, make up most of the human body, such as skin and muscle cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Cells differentiate to specialize for different functions.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Germ line cells are any line of cells that give rise to gametes—eggs and sperm—and thus are continuous through the generations.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Stem cells, on the other hand, have the ability to divide for indefinite periods and to give rise to specialized cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] They are best described in the context of normal human development.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Development begins when a sperm fertilizes an egg and creates a single cell that has the potential to form an entire organism.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In the first hours after fertilization, this cell divides into identical cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In humans, approximately four days after fertilization and after several cycles of cell division, these cells begin to specialize, forming a hollow sphere of cells, called a blastocyst.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The blastocyst has an outer layer of cells, and inside this hollow sphere, there is a cluster of cells called the inner cell mass.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The cells of the inner cell mass go on to form virtually all of the tissues of the human body.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Although the cells of the inner cell mass can form virtually every type of cell found in the human body, they cannot form an organism.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] These cells are referred to as pluripotent.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Pluripotent stem cells undergo further specialization into multipotent progenitor cells that then give rise to functional cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The ectoderm ends up forming the skin and the nervous system, the mesoderm forms the bones and muscular tissue, and the endoderm forms the internal organ tissues.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Dedifferentiation, or integration, is a cellular process seen in the more basal life forms in animals, such as worms and amphibians where a differentiated cell reverts to an earlier developmental stage—usually as part of a regenerative process.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Dedifferentiation also occurs in plant cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] And, in cell culture in the laboratory, cells can change shape or may lose specific properties such as protein expression—which processes are also termed dedifferentiation.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Some hypothesize that dedifferentiation is an aberration that likely results in cancers, but others explain it as a natural part of the immune response that was lost to humans at some point of evolution.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The molecule reversine, a purine analog, has proven to induce dedifferentiation in myotubes.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] These manifestly dedifferentiated cells—now performing essentially as stem cells—could then redifferentiate into osteoblasts and adipocytes.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Each specialized cell type in an organism expresses a subset of all the genes that constitute the genome of that species.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Each cell type is defined by its particular pattern of regulated gene expression.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Cell differentiation is thus a transition of a cell from one cell type to another and it involves a switch from one pattern of gene expression to another.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Cellular differentiation during development can be understood as the result of a gene regulatory network.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] A regulatory gene and its cis-regulatory modules are nodes in a gene regulatory network; they receive input and create output elsewhere in the network.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The systems biology approach to developmental biology emphasizes the importance of investigating how developmental mechanisms interact to produce predictable patterns (morphogenesis).
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] However, recent research suggests there may be an alternative view.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Based on stochastic gene expression, cellular differentiation is the result of a Darwinian selective process occurring among cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In this frame, protein and gene networks are the result of cellular processes and not their cause.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Cellular differentiation is often controlled by cell signaling.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Many of the signal molecules that convey information from cell to cell during the control of cellular differentiation are called growth factors.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Although the details of specific signal transduction pathways vary, these pathways often share the following general steps.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] A ligand produced by one cell binds to a receptor in the extracellular region of another cell, inducing a conformational change in the receptor.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The shape of the cytoplasmic domain of the receptor changes, and the receptor acquires enzymatic activity.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The receptor then catalyzes reactions that phosphorylate other proteins, activating them.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] A cascade of phosphorylation reactions eventually activates a dormant transcription factor or cytoskeletal protein, thus contributing to the differentiation process in the target cell.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Cells and tissues can vary in competence, their ability to respond to external signals.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Signal induction refers to cascades of signaling events, during which a cell or tissue signals to another cell or tissue to influence its developmental fate.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Yamamoto and Jeffery investigated the role of the lens in eye formation in cave- and surface-dwelling fish, a striking example of induction.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Through reciprocal transplants, Yamamoto and Jeffery found that the lens vesicle of surface fish can induce other parts of the eye to develop in cave- and surface-dwelling fish, while the lens vesicle of the cave-dwelling fish cannot.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Other important mechanisms fall under the category of asymmetric cell divisions, divisions that give rise to daughter cells with distinct developmental fates.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Asymmetric cell divisions can occur because of asymmetrically expressed maternal **cytoplasmic determinants** or because of signaling.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In the former mechanism, distinct daughter cells are created during cytokinesis because of an uneven distribution of regulatory molecules in the parent cell; the distinct cytoplasm that each daughter cell inherits results in a distinct pattern of differentiation for each daughter cell.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] A well-studied example of pattern formation by asymmetric divisions is body axis patterning in Drosophila.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] RNA molecules are an important type of intracellular differentiation control signal.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The molecular and genetic basis of asymmetric cell divisions has also been studied in green algae of the genus *Volvox*, a model system for studying how unicellular organisms can evolve into multicellular organisms.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In *Volvox carteri*, the 16 cells in the anterior hemisphere of a 32-cell embryo divide asymmetrically, each producing one large and one small daughter cell.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The size of the cell at the end of all cell divisions determines whether it becomes a specialized germ or somatic cell.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] While evolutionarily conserved molecular processes are involved in the cellular mechanisms underlying these switches, in animal species these are very different from the well-characterized gene regulatory mechanisms of bacteria, and even from those of the animals' closest unicellular relatives.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Specifically, cell differentiation in animals is highly dependent on biomolecular condensates of regulatory proteins and enhancer DNA sequences.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Since each cell, regardless of cell type, possesses the same genome, determination of cell type must occur at the level of gene expression.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] While the regulation of gene expression can occur through cis- and trans-regulatory elements including a gene's promoter and enhancers, the problem arises as to how this expression pattern is maintained over numerous generations of cell division.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] As it turns out, epigenetic processes play a crucial role in regulating the decision to adopt a stem, progenitor, or mature cell fate.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] This section will focus primarily on mammalian stem cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In systems biology and mathematical modeling of gene regulatory networks, cell-fate determination is predicted to exhibit certain dynamics, such as attractor-convergence (the attractor can be an equilibrium point, limit cycle or strange attractor) or oscillatory.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The first question that can be asked is the extent and complexity of the role of epigenetic processes in the determination of cell fate.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] A clear answer to this question can be seen in the 2011 paper by Lister R, *et al.* on aberrant epigenomic programming in human induced pluripotent stem cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] As induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) are thought to mimic embryonic stem cells in their pluripotent properties, few epigenetic differences should exist between them.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] To test this prediction, the authors conducted whole-genome profiling of DNA methylation patterns in several human embryonic stem cell (ESC), iPSC, and progenitor cell lines.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Female adipose cells, lung fibroblasts, and foreskin fibroblasts were reprogrammed into induced pluripotent state with the OCT4, SOX2, KLF4, and MYC genes.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Patterns of DNA methylation in ESCs, iPSCs, somatic cells were compared.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Lister R, *et al.* observed significant resemblance in methylation levels between embryonic and induced pluripotent cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Around 80% of CG dinucleotides in ESCs and iPSCs were methylated, the same was true of only 60% of CG dinucleotides in somatic cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In addition, somatic cells possessed minimal levels of cytosine methylation in non-CG dinucleotides, while induced pluripotent cells possessed similar levels of methylation as embryonic stem cells, between 0.5 and 1.5%.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Thus, consistent with their respective transcriptional activities, DNA methylation patterns, at least on the genomic level, are similar between ESCs and iPSCs.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] However, upon examining methylation patterns more closely, the authors discovered 1175 regions of differential CG dinucleotide methylation between at least one ES or iPS cell line.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In vitro-induced differentiation of iPSC lines saw transmission of 88% and 46% of hyper and hypo-methylated differentially methylated regions, respectively.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Two conclusions are readily apparent from this study.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] First, epigenetic processes are heavily involved in cell fate determination, as seen from the similar levels of cytosine methylation between induced pluripotent and embryonic stem cells, consistent with their respective patterns of transcription.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Second, the mechanisms of reprogramming (and by extension, differentiation) are very complex and cannot be easily duplicated, as seen by the significant number of differentially methylated regions between ES and iPS cell lines.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Now that these two points have been established, we can examine some of the epigenetic mechanisms that are thought to regulate cellular differentiation.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Three transcription factors, OCT4, SOX2, and NANOG – the first two of which are used in induced pluripotent stem cell (iPSC) reprogramming, along with Klf4 and c-Myc – are highly expressed in undifferentiated embryonic stem cells and are necessary for the maintenance of their pluripotency.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] It is thought that they achieve this through alterations in chromatin structure, such as histone modification and DNA methylation, to restrict or permit the transcription of target genes.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] While highly expressed, their levels require a precise balance to maintain pluripotency, perturbation of which will promote differentiation towards different lineages based on how the gene expression levels change.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Differential regulation of Oct-4 and SOX2 levels have been shown to precede germ layer fate selection.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Increased levels of Oct4 and decreased levels of Sox2 promote a mesendodermal fate, with Oct4 actively suppressing genes associated with a neural ectodermal fate.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Similarly, increased levels of Sox2 and decreased levels of Oct4 promote differentiation towards a neural ectodermal fate, with Sox2 inhibiting differentiation towards a mesendodermal fate.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Regardless of the lineage cells differentiate down, suppression of NANOG has been identified as a necessary prerequisite for differentiation.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In the realm of gene silencing, Polycomb repressive complex 2, one of two classes of the Polycomb group (PcG) family of proteins, catalyzes the di- and tri-methylation of histone H3 lysine 27 (H3K27me2/me3).
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] By binding to the H3K27me2/3-tagged nucleosome, PRC1 (also a complex of PcG family proteins) catalyzes the mono-ubiquitinylation of histone H2A at lysine 119 (H2AK119Ub1), blocking RNA polymerase II activity and resulting in transcriptional suppression.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] PcG knockout ES cells do not differentiate efficiently into the three germ layers, and deletion of the PRC1 and PRC2 genes leads to increased expression of lineage-affiliated genes and unscheduled differentiation.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Presumably, PcG complexes are responsible for transcriptionally repressing differentiation and development-promoting genes.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Alternately, upon receiving differentiation signals, PcG proteins are recruited to promoters of pluripotency transcription factors.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] PcG-deficient ES cells can begin differentiation but cannot maintain the differentiated phenotype.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Simultaneously, differentiation and development-promoting genes are activated by Trithorax group (TrxG) chromatin regulators and lose their repression.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] TrxG proteins are recruited at regions of high transcriptional activity, where they catalyze the trimethylation of histone H3 lysine 4 (H3K4me3) and promote gene activation through histone acetylation.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] PcG and TrxG complexes engage in direct competition and are thought to be functionally antagonistic, creating at differentiation and development-promoting loci what is termed a "bivalent domain" and rendering these genes sensitive to rapid induction or repression.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Regulation of gene expression is further achieved through DNA methylation, in which the DNA methyltransferase-mediated methylation of cytosine residues in CpG dinucleotides maintains heritable repression by controlling DNA accessibility.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The majority of CpG sites in embryonic stem cells are unmethylated and appear to be associated with H3K4me3-carrying nucleosomes.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Upon differentiation, a small number of genes, including OCT4 and NANOG, are methylated and their promoters repressed to prevent their further expression.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Consistently, DNA methylation-deficient embryonic stem cells rapidly enter apoptosis upon in vitro differentiation.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] While the DNA sequence of most cells of an organism is the same, the binding patterns of transcription factors and the corresponding gene expression patterns are different.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] To a large extent, differences in transcription factor binding are determined by the chromatin accessibility of their binding sites through histone modification and/or pioneer factors.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In particular, it is important to know whether a nucleosome is covering a given genomic binding site or not.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] This can be determined using a chromatin immunoprecipitation assay.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] DNA-nucleosome interactions are characterized by two states: either tightly bound by nucleosomes and transcriptionally inactive, called heterochromatin, or loosely bound and usually, but not always, transcriptionally active, called euchromatin.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The epigenetic processes of histone methylation and acetylation, and their inverses demethylation and deacetylation primarily account for these changes.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The effects of acetylation and deacetylation are more predictable.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] An acetyl group is either added to or removed from the positively charged Lysine residues in histones by enzymes called histone acetyltransferases or histone deactylases, respectively.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The acetyl group prevents Lysine's association with the negatively charged DNA backbone.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Methylation is not as straightforward, as neither methylation nor demethylation consistently correlate with either gene activation or repression.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] However, certain methylations have been repeatedly shown to either activate or repress genes.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The trimethylation of lysine 4 on histone 3 (H3K4Me3) is associated with gene activation, whereas trimethylation of lysine 27 on histone 3 represses genes.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] During differentiation, stem cells change their gene expression profiles.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Recent studies have implicated a role for nucleosome positioning and histone modifications during this process.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] There are two components of this process: turning off the expression of embryonic stem cell (ESC) genes, and the activation of cell fate genes.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Lysine specific demethylase 1 (KDM1A) is thought to prevent the use of enhancer regions of pluripotency genes, thereby inhibiting their transcription.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] It interacts with Mi-2/NuRD complex (nucleosome remodelling and histone deacetylase) complex, giving an instance where methylation and acetylation are not discrete and mutually exclusive, but intertwined processes.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] A final question to ask concerns the role of cell signaling in influencing the epigenetic processes governing differentiation.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Such a role should exist, as it would be reasonable to think that extrinsic signaling can lead to epigenetic remodeling, just as it can lead to changes in gene expression through the activation or repression of different transcription factors.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Little direct data is available concerning the specific signals that influence the epigenome, and the majority of current knowledge about the subject consists of speculations on plausible candidate regulators of epigenetic remodeling.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] We will first discuss several major candidates thought to be involved in the induction and maintenance of both embryonic stem cells and their differentiated progeny, and then turn to one example of specific signaling pathways in which more direct evidence exists for its role in epigenetic change.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The first major candidate is Wnt signaling pathway.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The Wnt pathway is involved in all stages of differentiation, and the ligand Wnt3a can substitute for the overexpression of c-Myc in the generation of induced pluripotent stem cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] On the other hand, disruption of β-catenin, a component of the Wnt signaling pathway, leads to decreased proliferation of neural progenitors.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Growth factors comprise the second major set of candidates of epigenetic regulators of cellular differentiation.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] These morphogens are crucial for development, and include bone morphogenetic proteins, transforming growth factors (TGFs), and fibroblast growth factors (FGFs).
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] TGFs and FGFs have been shown to sustain expression of OCT4, SOX2, and NANOG by downstream signaling to Smad proteins.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Depletion of growth factors promotes the differentiation of ESCs, while genes with bivalent chromatin can become either more restrictive or permissive in their transcription.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Several other signaling pathways are also considered to be primary candidates.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Cytokine leukemia inhibitory factors are associated with the maintenance of mouse ESCs in an undifferentiated state.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] This is achieved through its activation of the Jak-STAT3 pathway, which has been shown to be necessary and sufficient towards maintaining mouse ESC pluripotency.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Retinoic acid can induce differentiation of human and mouse ESCs, and Notch signaling is involved in the proliferation and self-renewal of stem cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Finally, Sonic hedgehog, in addition to its role as a morphogen, promotes embryonic stem cell differentiation and the self-renewal of somatic stem cells.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The problem, of course, is that the candidacy of these signaling pathways was inferred primarily on the basis of their role in development and cellular differentiation.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] While epigenetic regulation is necessary for driving cellular differentiation, they are certainly not sufficient for this process.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Direct modulation of gene expression through modification of transcription factors plays a key role that must be distinguished from heritable epigenetic changes that can persist even in the absence of the original environmental signals.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Only a few examples of signaling pathways leading to epigenetic changes that alter cell fate currently exist, and we will focus on one of them.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Expression of Shh (Sonic hedgehog) upregulates the production of BMI1, a component of the PcG complex that recognizes H3K27me3.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] This occurs in a Gli-dependent manner, as Gli1 and Gli2 are downstream effectors of the Hedgehog signaling pathway.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In culture, Bmi1 mediates the Hedgehog pathway's ability to promote human mammary stem cell self-renewal.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In both humans and mice, researchers showed Bmi1 to be highly expressed in proliferating immature cerebellar granule cell precursors.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] When Bmi1 was knocked out in mice, impaired cerebellar development resulted, leading to significant reductions in postnatal brain mass along with abnormalities in motor control and behavior.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] A separate study showed a significant decrease in neural stem cell proliferation along with increased astrocyte proliferation in Bmi null mice.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] An alternative model of cellular differentiation during embryogenesis is that positional information is based on mechanical signalling by the cytoskeleton using Embryonic differentiation waves.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The mechanical signal is then epigenetically transduced via signal transduction systems (of which specific molecules such as Wnt are part) to result in differential gene expression.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In summary, the role of signaling in the epigenetic control of cell fate in mammals is largely unknown, but distinct examples exist that indicate the likely existence of further such mechanisms.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] In order to fulfill the purpose of regenerating a variety of tissues, adult stems are known to migrate from their niches, adhere to new extracellular matrices (ECM) and differentiate.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The ductility of these microenvironments are unique to different tissue types.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The ECM surrounding brain, muscle and bone tissues range from soft to stiff.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The transduction of the stem cells into these cells types is not directed solely by chemokine cues and cell to cell signaling.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The elasticity of the microenvironment can also affect the differentiation of mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs which originate in bone marrow.) When MSCs are placed on substrates of the same stiffness as brain, muscle and bone ECM, the MSCs take on properties of those respective cell types.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Matrix sensing requires the cell to pull against the matrix at focal adhesions, which triggers a cellular mechano-transducer to generate a signal to be informed what force is needed to deform the matrix.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] To determine the key players in matrix-elasticity-driven lineage specification in MSCs, different matrix microenvironments were mimicked.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] From these experiments, it was concluded that focal adhesions of the MSCs were the cellular mechano-transducer sensing the differences of the matrix elasticity.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The non-muscle myosin IIa-c isoforms generates the forces in the cell that lead to signaling of early commitment markers.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Nonmuscle myosin IIa generates the least force increasing to non-muscle myosin IIc.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] There are also factors in the cell that inhibit non-muscle myosin II, such as blebbistatin.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] This makes the cell effectively blind to the surrounding matrix.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] Researchers have achieved some success in inducing stem cell-like properties in HEK 239 cells by providing a soft matrix without the use of diffusing factors.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The stem-cell properties appear to be linked to tension in the cells' actin network.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] One identified mechanism for matrix-induced differentiation is tension-induced proteins, which remodel chromatin in response to mechanical stretch.
[src:organoids/cellular-differentiation] The RhoA pathway is also implicated in this process.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] In biology, the **extracellular matrix** (**ECM**), also called the **intercellular matrix**, is a network consisting of extracellular macromolecules and minerals, such as collagen, enzymes, glycoproteins and hydroxyapatite that provide structural and biochemical support to surrounding cells.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Because multicellularity evolved independently in different multicellular lineages, the composition of ECM varies between multicellular structures; however, cell adhesion, cell-to-cell communication and differentiation are common functions of the ECM.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The animal extracellular matrix includes the interstitial matrix and the basement membrane.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Interstitial matrix is present in the intercellular spaces between various animal cells.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Gels of polysaccharides and fibrous proteins fill the interstitial space and act as a compression buffer against the stress placed on the ECM.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Basement membranes are sheet-like depositions of ECM on which various epithelial cells rest.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Each type of connective tissue in animals has a type of ECM: collagen fibers and bone mineral comprise the ECM of bone tissue; reticular fibers and ground substance comprise the ECM of loose connective tissue; and blood plasma is the ECM of blood.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The plant ECM includes cell wall components, like cellulose, in addition to more complex signaling molecules.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Some microorganisms adopt multicellular biofilms in which the cells are embedded in an ECM composed primarily of extracellular polymeric substances.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Components of the ECM are produced intracellularly by resident cells and secreted into the ECM via exocytosis.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Once secreted, they then aggregate with the existing matrix.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The ECM is composed of an interlocking mesh of fibrous proteins and glycosaminoglycans (GAGs).
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Glycosaminoglycans (GAGs) are carbohydrate polymers and mostly attached to extracellular matrix proteins to form proteoglycans (hyaluronic acid is a notable exception; see below).
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Proteoglycans have a net negative charge that attracts positively charged sodium ions (Na+), which attracts water molecules via osmosis, keeping the ECM and resident cells hydrated.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Proteoglycans may also help to trap and store growth factors within the ECM.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Described below are the different types of proteoglycan found within the extracellular matrix.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Heparan sulfate (HS) is a linear polysaccharide found in all animal tissues.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] It occurs as a proteoglycan in which two or three HS chains are attached in close proximity to cell surface or ECM proteins.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] It is in this form that HS binds to a variety of protein ligands and regulates a wide variety of biological activities, including developmental processes, angiogenesis, blood coagulation, and tumour metastasis.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] In the extracellular matrix, especially basement membranes, the multi-domain proteins perlecan, agrin, and collagen XVIII are the main proteins to which heparan sulfate is attached.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Chondroitin sulfates contribute to the tensile strength of cartilage, tendons, ligaments, and walls of the aorta.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] They have also been known to affect neuroplasticity.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Keratan sulfates have a variable sulfate content and, unlike many other GAGs, do not contain uronic acid.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] They are present in the cornea, cartilage, bones, and the horns of animals.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Hyaluronic acid (or "hyaluronan") is a polysaccharide consisting of alternating residues of D-glucuronic acid and N-acetylglucosamine, and unlike other GAGs, is not found as a proteoglycan.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Hyaluronic acid in the extracellular space confers upon tissues the ability to resist compression by providing a counteracting turgor (swelling) force by absorbing significant amounts of water.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Hyaluronic acid is thus found in abundance in the ECM of load-bearing joints.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] It is also a chief component of the interstitial gel.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Hyaluronic acid is found on the inner surface of the cell membrane and is translocated out of the cell during biosynthesis.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Hyaluronic acid acts as an environmental cue that regulates cell behavior during embryonic development, healing processes, inflammation, and tumor development.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] It interacts with a specific transmembrane receptor, CD44.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Chitin, a polymer of N-acetyl glucosamine, is not produced by mammals but is used extensively by various groups of invertebrates.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] It is an essential part of the shell of mulloscs, the cuticle of arthropods, the fibrous ECM of sponges, and the squid beak.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Chitin forms into fibers and the fibers are organized into one of three crystalline shapes, α/β/γ.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The chitin in arthropods and sponges are mostly in the α shape, organized into sheets (laminae) with the help of β-sheet-rich chitin-binding proteins.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The chitin in squid beak is in the β form, organized into a hard composite material with protein coacervates.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Chitin also makes up the cell wall of fungi.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The stomachs of mammals (including humans) produce chitinase (acidic mammalian chitinase, AMCase), allowing them to break down chitin found in the diet.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Despite being digestible, chitin also acts as a dietary fiber in mammals.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The production of AMCase requries an immune response to be mounted against chitin.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Collagen is the most abundant protein in the ECM, and is the most abundant protein in the human body.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] It accounts for 90% of bone matrix protein content.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Collagens are present in the ECM as fibrillar proteins and give structural support to resident cells.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Collagen is exocytosed in precursor form (procollagen), which is then cleaved by procollagen proteases to allow extracellular assembly.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Disorders such as Ehlers Danlos Syndrome, osteogenesis imperfecta, and epidermolysis bullosa are linked with genetic defects in collagen-encoding genes.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Elastins, in contrast to collagens, give elasticity to tissues, allowing them to stretch when needed and then return to their original state.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] This is useful in blood vessels, the lungs, in skin, and the ligamentum nuchae, and these tissues contain high amounts of elastins.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Elastins are synthesized by fibroblasts and smooth muscle cells.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Elastins are highly insoluble, and tropoelastins are secreted inside a chaperone molecule, which releases the precursor molecule upon contact with a fiber of mature elastin.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Tropoelastins are then deaminated to become incorporated into the elastin strand.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Disorders such as cutis laxa and Williams syndrome are associated with deficient or absent elastin fibers in the ECM.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] In 2016, Huleihel et al., reported the presence of DNA, RNA, and Matrix-bound nanovesicles (MBVs) within ECM bioscaffolds.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] MBVs shape and size were found to be consistent with previously described exosomes.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] MBVs cargo includes different protein molecules, lipids, DNA, fragments, and miRNAs.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Similar to ECM bioscaffolds, MBVs can modify the activation state of macrophages and alter different cellular properties such as; proliferation, migration and cell cycle.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] MBVs are now believed to be an integral and functional key component of ECM bioscaffolds.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Fibronectins are glycoproteins that connect cells with collagen fibers in the ECM, allowing cells to move through the ECM.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Fibronectins bind collagen and cell-surface integrins, causing a reorganization of the cell's cytoskeleton to facilitate cell movement.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Fibronectins are secreted by cells in an unfolded, inactive form.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Binding to integrins unfolds fibronectin molecules, allowing them to form dimers so that they can function properly.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Fibronectins also help at the site of tissue injury by binding to platelets during blood clotting and facilitating cell movement to the affected area during wound healing.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Laminins are proteins found in the basal laminae of virtually all animals.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Rather than forming collagen-like fibers, laminins form networks of web-like structures that resist tensile forces in the basal lamina.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Laminins bind other ECM components such as collagens and nidogens.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] There are many cell types that contribute to the development of the various types of extracellular matrix found in the plethora of tissue types.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The local components of ECM determine the properties of the connective tissue.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Fibroblasts are the most common cell type in connective tissue ECM, in which they synthesize, maintain, and provide a structural framework; fibroblasts secrete the precursor components of the ECM, including the ground substance.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Chondrocytes are found in cartilage and produce the cartilaginous matrix.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Osteoblasts are responsible for bone formation.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The ECM can exist in varying degrees of stiffness and elasticity, from soft brain tissues to hard bone tissues.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The elasticity of the ECM can differ by several orders of magnitude.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] This property is primarily dependent on collagen and elastin concentrations, and it has recently been shown to play an influential role in regulating numerous cell functions.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Cells can sense the mechanical properties of their environment by applying forces and measuring the resulting backlash.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] This plays an important role because it helps regulate many important cellular processes including cellular contraction, cell migration, cell proliferation, differentiation and cell death (apoptosis).
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Inhibition of nonmuscle myosin II blocks most of these effects, indicating that they are indeed tied to sensing the mechanical properties of the ECM, which has become a new focus in research during the past decade.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Differing mechanical properties in ECM exert effects on both cell behaviour and gene expression.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Although the mechanism by which this is done has not been thoroughly explained, adhesion complexes and the actin-myosin cytoskeleton, whose contractile forces are transmitted through transcellular structures are thought to play key roles in the yet to be discovered molecular pathways.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] ECM elasticity can direct cellular differentiation, the process by which a cell changes from one cell type to another.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] In particular, naive mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) have been shown to specify lineage and commit to phenotypes with extreme sensitivity to tissue-level elasticity.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] MSCs placed on soft matrices that mimic the brain differentiate into neuron-like cells, showing similar shape, RNAi profiles, cytoskeletal markers, and transcription factor levels.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Similarly stiffer matrices that mimic muscle are myogenic, and matrices with stiffnesses that mimic collagenous bone are osteogenic.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Stiffness and elasticity also guide cell migration, this process is called durotaxis.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The term was coined by Lo CM and colleagues when they discovered the tendency of single cells to migrate up rigidity gradients (towards more stiff substrates) and has been extensively studied since.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The molecular mechanisms behind durotaxis are thought to exist primarily in the focal adhesion, a large protein complex that acts as the primary site of contact between the cell and the ECM.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] This complex contains many proteins that are essential to durotaxis including structural anchoring proteins (integrins) and signaling proteins (adhesion kinase (FAK), talin, vinculin, paxillin, α-actinin, GTPases etc.) which cause changes in cell shape and actomyosin contractility.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] These changes are thought to cause cytoskeletal rearrangements in order to facilitate directional migration.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Due to its diverse nature and composition, the ECM can serve many functions, such as providing support, segregating tissues from one another, and regulating intercellular communication.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The extracellular matrix regulates a cell's dynamic behavior.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] In addition, it sequesters a wide range of cellular growth factors and acts as a local store for them.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Changes in physiological conditions can trigger protease activities that cause local release of such stores.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] This allows the rapid local growth-factor-mediated activation of cellular functions without *de novo* synthesis.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Formation of the extracellular matrix is essential for processes like growth, wound healing, and fibrosis.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The stiffness and elasticity of the ECM has important implications in cell migration, gene expression, and differentiation.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Cells actively sense ECM rigidity and migrate preferentially towards stiffer surfaces in a phenomenon called durotaxis.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] They also detect elasticity and adjust their gene expression accordingly, which has increasingly become a subject of research because of its impact on differentiation and cancer progression.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The biochemical and biomechanical properties of tumor ECM differ from those of normal tissues, and could be used for cancer diagnosis and therapy.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] In the brain, hyaluronan serves as the primary component of the extracellular matrix, contributing to both structural integrity and signaling functions.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] High-molecular-weight hyaluronan forms a diffusional barrier that regulates local extracellular diffusion.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] When the ECM undergoes degradation, hyaluronan fragments are released into the extracellular space, where they act as pro-inflammatory molecules, influencing immune cell responses, including those of microglia.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Many cells bind to components of the extracellular matrix.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Cell adhesion can occur in two ways; by focal adhesions, connecting the ECM to actin filaments of the cell, and hemidesmosomes, connecting the ECM to intermediate filaments such as keratin.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] This cell-to-ECM adhesion is regulated by specific cell-surface cellular adhesion molecules (CAM) known as integrins.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Integrins are cell-surface proteins that bind cells to ECM structures, such as fibronectin and laminin, and also to integrin proteins on the surface of other cells.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Fibronectins bind to ECM macromolecules and facilitate their binding to transmembrane integrins.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The attachment of fibronectin to the extracellular domain initiates intracellular signalling pathways as well as association with the cellular cytoskeleton via a set of adaptor molecules such as actin.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Extracellular matrix has been found to cause regrowth and healing of tissue.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Although the mechanism of action by which extracellular matrix promotes constructive remodeling of tissue is still unknown, researchers now believe that Matrix-bound nanovesicles (MBVs) are a key player in the healing process.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] In human fetuses, for example, the extracellular matrix works with stem cells to grow and regrow all parts of the human body, and fetuses can regrow anything that gets damaged in the womb.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Scientists have long believed that the matrix stops functioning after full development.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] It has been used in the past to help horses heal torn ligaments, but it is being researched further as a device for tissue regeneration in humans.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] In terms of injury repair and tissue engineering, the extracellular matrix serves two main purposes.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] First, it prevents the immune system from triggering from the injury and responding with inflammation and scar tissue.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Next, it facilitates the surrounding cells to repair the tissue instead of forming scar tissue.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] For medical applications, the required ECM is usually extracted from pig bladders, an easily accessible and relatively unused source.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] It is currently being used regularly to treat ulcers by closing the hole in the tissue that lines the stomach, but further research is currently being done by many universities as well as the U.S.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Government for wounded soldier applications.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] As of early 2007, testing was being carried out on a military base in Texas.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Scientists are using a powdered form on Iraq War veterans whose hands were damaged in the war.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Not all ECM devices come from the bladder.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Extracellular matrix coming from pig small intestine submucosa are being used to repair "atrial septal defects" (ASD), "patent foramen ovale" (PFO) and inguinal hernia.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] After one year, 95% of the collagen ECM in these patches has been replaced by the body with the normal soft tissue of the heart.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Extracellular matrix proteins are commonly used in cell culture systems to maintain stem and precursor cells in an undifferentiated state during cell culture and function to induce differentiation of epithelial, endothelial and smooth muscle cells in vitro.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Extracellular matrix proteins can also be used to support 3D cell culture in vitro for modelling tumor development.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] A class of biomaterials derived from processing human or animal tissues to retain portions of the extracellular matrix are called ECM Biomaterial.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Plant cells are tessellated to form tissues.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The cell wall is the relatively rigid structure surrounding the plant cell.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The cell wall provides lateral strength to resist osmotic turgor pressure, but it is flexible enough to allow cell growth when needed; it also serves as a medium for intercellular communication.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The cell wall comprises multiple laminate layers of cellulose microfibrils embedded in a matrix of glycoproteins, including hemicellulose, pectin, and extensin.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The components of the glycoprotein matrix help cell walls of adjacent plant cells to bind to each other.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The selective permeability of the cell wall is chiefly governed by pectins in the glycoprotein matrix.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] Plasmodesmata (*singular*: plasmodesma) are pores that traverse the cell walls of adjacent plant cells.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] These channels are tightly regulated and selectively allow molecules of specific sizes to pass between cells.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The extracellular matrix functionality of animals (Metazoa) developed in the common ancestor of the Pluriformea and Filozoa, after the Ichthyosporea diverged.
[src:organoids/extracellular-matrix] The importance of the extracellular matrix has long been recognized (Lewis, 1922), but the usage of the term is more recent (Gospodarowicz et al., 1979).
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Pluripotent stem cells hold promise in the field of regenerative medicine.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Because they can propagate indefinitely, as well as give rise to every other cell type in the body (such as neurons, heart, pancreatic, and liver cells), they represent a single source of cells that could be used to replace those lost to damage or disease.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The best-known type of pluripotent stem cell is the embryonic stem cell.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] However, since the generation of embryonic stem cells involves the destruction (or at least manipulation) of a pre-implantation stage embryo, there has been much controversy surrounding their use.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Patient-matched embryonic stem cell lines can now be derived using somatic cell nuclear transfer (SCNT).
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Since iPSCs can be derived directly from adult tissues, they not only bypass the need for embryos, but can be made in a patient-matched manner, which means that each individual could have their own pluripotent stem cell line.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These unlimited supplies of autologous cells could be used to generate transplants without the risk of immune rejection.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] While the iPSC technology has not yet advanced to a stage where therapeutic transplants have been deemed safe, iPSCs are readily being used in personalized drug discovery efforts and understanding the patient-specific basis of disease.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Yamanaka named iPSCs with a lower case "i" due to the popularity of the iPod and other Apple products.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In his Nobel seminar, Yamanaka cited the earlier seminal work of Harold Weintraub on the role of myoblast determination protein 1 (MyoD) in reprogramming cell fate to a muscle lineage as an important precursor to the discovery of iPSCs.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] iPSCs are typically derived by introducing products of specific sets of pluripotency-associated genes, or "reprogramming factors", into a given cell type.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The original set of reprogramming factors (also dubbed Yamanaka factors) are the transcription factors Oct4 (Pou5f1), Sox2, Klf4 and cMyc.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] While this combination is most conventional in producing iPSCs, each of the factors can be functionally replaced by related transcription factors, miRNAs, small molecules, or even non-related genes such as lineage specifiers.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] It is also clear that pro-mitotic factors such as C-MYC/L-MYC or repression of cell cycle checkpoints, such as p53, are conduits to creating a compliant cellular state for iPSC reprogramming.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] iPSC derivation is typically a slow and inefficient process, taking one–two weeks for mouse cells and three–four weeks for human cells, with efficiencies around 0.01–0.1%.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] However, considerable advances have been made in improving the efficiency and the time it takes to obtain iPSCs.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Upon introduction of reprogramming factors, cells begin to form colonies that resemble pluripotent stem cells, which can be isolated based on their morphology, conditions that select for their growth, or through expression of surface markers or reporter genes.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Induced pluripotent stem cells were first generated by Shinya Yamanaka and Kazutoshi Takahashi at Kyoto University, Japan, in 2006.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] They hypothesized that genes important to embryonic stem cell (ESC) function might be able to induce an embryonic state in adult cells.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] They chose twenty-four genes previously identified as important in ESCs and used retroviruses to deliver these genes to mouse fibroblasts.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The fibroblasts were engineered so that any cells reactivating the ESC-specific gene, Fbx15, could be isolated using antibiotic selection.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Upon delivery of all twenty-four factors, ESC-like colonies emerged that reactivated the Fbx15 reporter and could propagate indefinitely.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] To identify the genes necessary for reprogramming, the researchers removed one factor at a time from the pool of twenty-four.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] By this process, they identified four factors, Oct4, Sox2, cMyc, and Klf4, which were each necessary and together sufficient to generate ESC-like colonies under selection for reactivation of Fbx15.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In June 2007, three separate research groups, including that of Yamanaka's, a Harvard/University of California, Los Angeles collaboration, and a group at MIT, published studies that substantially improved on the reprogramming approach, giving rise to iPSCs that were indistinguishable from ESCs.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Unlike the first generation of iPSCs, these second generation iPSCs produced viable chimeric mice and contributed to the mouse germline, thereby achieving the 'gold standard' for pluripotent stem cells.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These second-generation iPSCs were derived from mouse fibroblasts by retroviral-mediated expression of the same four transcription factors (Oct4, Sox2, cMyc, Klf4).
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] However, instead of using Fbx15 to select for pluripotent cells, the researchers used Nanog, a gene that is functionally important in ESCs.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] By using this different strategy, the researchers created iPSCs that were functionally identical to ESCs.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Reprogramming of human cells to iPSCs was reported in November 2007 by two independent research groups: Shinya Yamanaka of Kyoto University, Japan, who pioneered the original iPSC method, and James Thomson of University of Wisconsin-Madison who was the first to derive human embryonic stem cells.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Obtaining fibroblasts to produce iPSCs involves a skin biopsy, and there has been a push towards identifying cell types that are more easily accessible.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2008, iPSCs were derived from human keratinocytes, which could be obtained from a single hair pluck.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2010, iPSCs were derived from peripheral blood cells, and in 2012, iPSCs were made from renal epithelial cells in the urine.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Other considerations for starting cell type include mutational load (for example, skin cells may harbor more mutations due to UV exposure), time it takes to expand the population of starting cells, and the ability to differentiate into a given cell type.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The generation of induced pluripotent cells is crucially dependent on the transcription factors used for the induction.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Oct-3/4 and certain products of the Sox gene family (Sox1, Sox2, Sox3, and Sox15) have been identified as crucial transcriptional regulators involved in the induction process whose absence makes induction impossible.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Additional genes, however, including certain members of the Klf family (Klf1, Klf2, Klf4, and Klf5), the Myc family (c-myc, L-myc, and N-myc), Nanog, and LIN28, have been identified to increase the induction efficiency.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Genomic Insertion: genomic integration of the transcription factors limits the utility of the transcription factor approach because of the risk of mutations being inserted into the target cell's genome.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] A common strategy for avoiding genomic insertion has been to use a different vector for input.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Plasmids, adenoviruses, and transposon vectors have all been explored, but these often come with the tradeoff of lower throughput.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Tumorigenicity: Depending on the methods used, reprogramming of adult cells to obtain iPSCs may pose significant risks that could limit their use in humans.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] For example, if viruses are used to genomically alter the cells, the expression of oncogenes (cancer-causing genes) may potentially be triggered.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In February 2008, scientists announced the discovery of a technique that could remove oncogenes after the induction of pluripotency, thereby increasing the potential use of iPS cells in human diseases.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In another study, Yamanaka reported that one can create iPSCs without the oncogene c-Myc.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The process took longer and was not as efficient, but the resulting chimeras did not develop cancer.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Inactivation or deletion of the tumor suppressor p53, which is a key regulator of cancer, significantly increases reprogramming efficiency.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Thus there seems to be a tradeoff between reprogramming efficiency and tumor generation.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Incomplete reprogramming: reprogramming also faces the challenge of completeness.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] This is particularly challenging because the genome-wide epigenetic code must be reformatted to that of the target cell type in order to fully reprogram a cell.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The table on the right summarizes the key strategies and techniques used to develop iPS cells in the first five years after Yamanaka et al.'s 2006 breakthrough.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Rows of similar colors represent studies that used similar strategies for reprogramming.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] One of the main strategies for avoiding problems (1) and (2) has been to use small molecules that can mimic the effects of transcription factors.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These compounds can compensate for a reprogramming factor that does not effectively target the genome or fails at reprogramming for another reason; thus they raise reprogramming efficiency.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] They also avoid the problem of genomic integration, which in some cases contributes to tumor genesis.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Key studies using such strategy were conducted in 2008.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Melton et al. studied the effects of histone deacetylase (HDAC) inhibitor valproic acid.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] They found that it increased reprogramming efficiency 100-fold (compared to Yamanaka's traditional transcription factor method).
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The researchers proposed that this compound was mimicking the signaling that is usually caused by the transcription factor c-Myc.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] A similar type of compensation mechanism was proposed to mimic the effects of Sox2.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2008, Ding et al. used the inhibition of histone methyl transferase (HMT) with BIX-01294 in combination with the activation of calcium channels in the plasma membrane in order to increase reprogramming efficiency.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Deng et al. of Beijing University reported in July 2013 that induced pluripotent stem cells can be created without any genetic modification.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] They used a cocktail of seven small-molecule compounds including DZNep to induce the mouse somatic cells into stem cells which they called CiPS cells with the efficiency – at 0.2% – comparable to those using standard iPSC production techniques.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The CiPS cells were introduced into developing mouse embryos and were found to contribute to all major cell types, proving its pluripotency.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Ding *et al*. demonstrated an alternative to transcription factor reprogramming through the use of drug-like chemicals.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Adding a third compound known to be involved in the cell survival pathway, thiazovivin further increases the efficiency by 200 fold.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Using the combination of these three compounds also decreased the reprogramming process of the human fibroblasts from four weeks to two weeks.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In April 2009, it was demonstrated that generation of iPS cells is possible without any genetic alteration of the adult cell: a repeated treatment of the cells with certain proteins channeled into the cells via poly-arginine anchors was sufficient to induce pluripotency.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The acronym given for those iPSCs is **piPSCs** (protein-induced pluripotent stem cells).
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Another key strategy for avoiding problems such as tumorgenesis and low throughput has been to use alternate forms of vectors: adenoviruses, plasmids, and naked DNA or protein compounds.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2008, Hochedlinger et al. used an adenovirus to transport the requisite four transcription factors into the DNA of skin and liver cells of mice, resulting in cells identical to ESCs.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The adenovirus is unique from other vectors like viruses and retroviruses because it does not incorporate any of its own genes into the targeted host and avoids the potential for insertional mutagenesis.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2009, Freed et al. demonstrated successful reprogramming of human fibroblasts to iPS cells.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Another advantage of using adenoviruses is that they only need to present for a brief amount of time in order for effective reprogramming to take place.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Also in 2008, Yamanaka et al. found that they could transfer the four necessary genes with a plasmid.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The Yamanaka group successfully reprogrammed mouse cells by transfection with two plasmid constructs carrying the reprogramming factors; the first plasmid expressed c-Myc, while the second expressed the other three factors (Oct4, Klf4, and Sox2).
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Although the plasmid methods avoid viruses, they still require cancer-promoting genes to accomplish reprogramming.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The other main issue with these methods is that they tend to be much less efficient compared to retroviral methods.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Furthermore, transfected plasmids have been shown to integrate into the host genome and therefore they still pose the risk of insertional mutagenesis.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Because non-retroviral approaches have demonstrated such low efficiency levels, researchers have attempted to effectively rescue the technique with what is known as the PiggyBac Transposon System.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Several studies have demonstrated that this system can effectively deliver the key reprogramming factors without leaving footprint mutations in the host cell genome.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The PiggyBac Transposon System involves the re-excision of exogenous genes, which eliminates the issue of insertional mutagenesis.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In light of difficulties that other labs had replicating the results of the surprising study, in March 2014, one of the co-authors has called for the articles to be retracted.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] On 4 June 2014, the lead author, Obokata agreed to retract both the papers after she was found to have committed 'research misconduct' as concluded in an investigation by RIKEN on 1 April 2014.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] MicroRNAs are short RNA molecules that bind to complementary sequences on messenger RNA and block expression of a gene.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Measuring variations in microRNA expression in iPS cells can be used to predict their differentiation potential.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Addition of microRNAs can also be used to enhance iPS potential.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] ES cell-specific microRNA molecules (such as miR-291, miR-294 and miR-295) enhance the efficiency of induced pluripotency by acting downstream of c-Myc.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] MicroRNAs can also block expression of repressors of Yamanaka's four transcription factors, and there may be additional mechanisms that induce reprogramming even in the absence of added exogenous transcription factors.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Gene expression and genome-wide H3K4me3 and H3K27me3 were found to be extremely similar between ES and iPS cells.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The task of producing iPS cells continues to be challenging due to the six problems mentioned above.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] A key tradeoff to overcome is that between efficiency and genomic integration.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Most methods that do not rely on the integration of transgenes are inefficient, while those that do rely on the integration of transgenes face the problems of incomplete reprogramming and tumor genesis, although a vast number of techniques and methods have been attempted.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Another large set of strategies is to perform a proteomic characterization of iPS cells.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Further studies and new strategies should generate optimal solutions to the five main challenges.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] One approach might attempt to combine the positive attributes of these strategies into an ultimately effective technique for reprogramming cells to iPS cells.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Another approach is the use of iPS cells derived from patients to identify therapeutic drugs able to rescue a phenotype.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] For instance, iPS cell lines derived from patients affected by ectodermal dysplasia syndrome (EEC), in which the p63 gene is mutated, display abnormal epithelial commitment that could be partially rescued by a small compound.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] An attractive feature of human iPS cells is the ability to derive them from adult patients to study the cellular basis of human disease.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Since iPS cells are self-renewing and pluripotent, they represent a theoretically unlimited source of patient-derived cells which can be turned into any type of cell in the body.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In many instances, the patient-derived iPS cells exhibit cellular defects not observed in iPS cells from healthy subjects, providing insight into the pathophysiology of the disease.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] An international collaborated project, StemBANCC, was formed in 2012 to build a collection of iPS cell lines for drug screening for a variety of diseases.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Managed by the University of Oxford, the effort pooled funds and resources from 10 pharmaceutical companies and 23 universities.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The goal is to generate a library of 1,500 iPS cell lines which will be used in early drug testing by providing a simulated human disease environment.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Furthermore, combining hiPSC technology and small molecule or genetically encoded voltage and calcium indicators provided a large-scale and high-throughput platform for cardiovascular drug safety screening.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] A proof-of-concept of using induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) to generate human organ for transplantation was reported by researchers from Japan.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Human 'liver buds' (iPSC-LBs) were grown from a mixture of three different kinds of stem cells: hepatocyte (for liver function) coaxed from iPSCs; endothelial stem cells (to form lining of blood vessels) from umbilical cord blood; and mesenchymal stem cells (to form connective tissue).
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] This new approach allows different cell types to self-organize into a complex organ, mimicking the process in fetal development.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] After growing *in vitro* for a few days, the liver buds were transplanted into mice where the 'liver' quickly connected with the host blood vessels and continued to grow.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Most importantly, it performed regular liver functions including metabolizing drugs and producing liver-specific proteins.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Further studies will monitor the longevity of the transplanted organ in the host body (ability to integrate or avoid rejection) and whether it will transform into tumors.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2021, a switchable Yamanaka factors-reprogramming-based approach for regeneration of damaged heart without tumor-formation was demonstrated in mice and was successful if the intervention was carried out immediately before or after a heart attack.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2020, Japan first transplanted lab-grown heart cells into a human patient.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Embryonic cord-blood cells were induced into pluripotent stem cells using plasmid DNA.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Using cell surface endothelial/pericytic markers CD31 and CD146, researchers identified 'vascular progenitor', the high-quality, multipotent vascular stem cells.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] After the iPS cells were injected directly into the vitreous of the damaged retina of mice, the stem cells engrafted into the retina, grew and repaired the vascular vessels.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Labelled iPSCs-derived NSCs injected into laboratory animals with brain lesions were shown to migrate to the lesions and some motor function improvement was observed.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Beating cardiac muscle cells, iPSC-derived cardiomyocytes, can be mass-produced using chemically defined differentiation protocols.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These protocols typically modulate the same developmental signaling pathways required for heart development.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These iPSC-cardiomyocytes can recapitulate genetic arrhythmias and cardiac drug responses, since they exhibit the same genetic background as the patient from which they were derived.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In June 2014, Takara Bio received technology transfer from iHeart Japan, a venture company from Kyoto University's iPS Cell Research Institute, to make it possible to exclusively use technologies and patents that induce differentiation of iPS cells into cardiomyocytes in Asia.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The company announced the idea of selling cardiomyocytes to pharmaceutical companies and universities to help develop new drugs for heart disease.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] On March 9, 2018, the Specified Regenerative Medicine Committee of Osaka University officially approved the world's first clinical research plan to transplant a "myocardial sheet" made from iPS cells into the heart of patients with severe heart failure.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Osaka University announced that it had filed an application with the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare on the same day.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] On May 16, 2018, the clinical research plan was approved by the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare's expert group with a condition.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In October 2019, a group at Okayama University developed a model of ischemic heart disease using cardiomyocytes differentiated from iPS cells.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Although a pint of donated blood contains about two trillion red blood cells and over 107 million blood donations are collected globally, there is still a critical need for blood for transfusion.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2014, type O red blood cells were synthesized at the Scottish National Blood Transfusion Service from iPSC.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The cells were induced to become a mesoderm and then blood cells and then red blood cells.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The final step was to make them eject their nuclei and mature properly.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Type O can be transfused into all patients.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Human clinical trials were not expected to begin before 2016.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The first human clinical trial using autologous iPSCs was approved by the Japan Ministry Health and was to be conducted in 2014 at the Riken Center for Developmental Biology in Kobe.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] However the trial was suspended after Japan's new regenerative medicine laws came into effect in November 2015.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] More specifically, an existing set of guidelines was strengthened to have the force of law (previously mere recommendations). iPSCs derived from skin cells from six patients with wet age-related macular degeneration were reprogrammed to differentiate into retinal pigment epithelial (RPE) cells.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The cell sheet would be transplanted into the affected retina where the degenerated RPE tissue was excised.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Safety and vision restoration monitoring were to last one to three years.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In March 2017, a team led by Masayo Takahashi completed the first successful transplant of iPS-derived retinal cells from a donor into the eye of a person with advanced macular degeneration.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] However it was reported that they are now having complications.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The benefits of using autologous iPSCs are that there is theoretically no risk of rejection and that it eliminates the need to use embryonic stem cells.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] However, these iPSCs were derived from another person.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] New clinical trials involving iPSCs are now ongoing not only in Japan, but also in the US and Europe.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Research in 2021 on the trial registry Clinicaltrials.gov identified 129 trial listings mentioning iPSCs, but most were non-interventional.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2026, Japan’s Pharmaceutical Affairs Council recommended that the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare extend conditional approval to two allogeneic iPSC-based therapeutic products, Amchepry for Parkinson’s and ReHeart for severe heart failure.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] To make iPSC-based regenerative medicine technologies available to more patients, it is necessary to create universal iPSCs that can be transplanted independently of haplotypes of HLA.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The current strategy for the creation of universal iPSCs has two main goals: to remove HLA expression and to prevent NK cells attacks due to deletion of HLA.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Deletion of the B2M and CIITA genes using the CRISPR/Cas9 system has been reported to suppress the expression of HLA class I and class II, respectively.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] To avoid NK cell attacks. transduction of ligands inhibiting NK-cells, such as HLA-E and CD47 has been used.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] HLA-C is left unchanged, since the 12 common HLA-C alleles are enough to cover 95% of the world's population.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] A multipotent mesenchymal stem cell, when induced into pluripotence, holds great promise to slow or reverse aging phenotypes.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Such anti-aging properties were demonstrated in early clinical trials in 2017.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2020, Stanford University researchers concluded after studying elderly mice that old human cells when subjected to the Yamanaka factors, might rejuvenate and become nearly indistinguishable from their younger counterparts.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] A review published in 2025 examines the development of hypoimmunogenic pluripotent stem cells (hPSCs) using advanced genome editing techniques aimed at reducing the risk of immune rejection in allogeneic cell therapy.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These hPSCs are engineered to lack expression of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) class I and II molecules, while expressing immune-modulatory genes such as PD-L1, CD47, and HLA-G.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] This combination enhances immune evasion and supports the concept of universal donor cells that do not require human leukocyte antigen (HLA) matching.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The integration of suicide gene systems, such as inducible Caspase-9, further enhances safety by enabling the selective elimination of cells in the event of malignancy.
[src:organoids/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These strategies are intended to improve the safety, scalability, and accessibility of regenerative treatments.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] An **organ-on-a-chip** (**OOC**) is a multi-channel 3D microfluidic cell culture, integrated circuit (chip) that simulates the activities, mechanics and physiological response of an entire organ or an organ system.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] It constitutes the subject matter of significant biomedical engineering research, more precisely in bio-MEMS.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The convergence of labs-on-chips (LOCs) and cell biology has permitted the study of human physiology in an organ-specific context.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] By acting as a more sophisticated *in vitro* approximation of complex tissues than standard cell culture, they provide the potential as an alternative to animal models for drug development and toxin testing.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Although multiple publications claim to have translated organ functions onto this interface, the development of these microfluidic applications is still in its infancy.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Organs-on-chips vary in design and approach between different researchers.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Organs that have been simulated by microfluidic devices include brain, lung, heart, kidney, liver, prostate, vessel (artery), skin, bone, cartilage and more.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] A limitation of the early organ-on-a-chip approach is that simulation of an isolated organ may miss significant biological phenomena that occur in the body's complex network of physiological processes, and that this oversimplification limits the inferences that can be drawn.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Many aspects of subsequent microphysiometry aim to address these constraints by modeling more sophisticated physiological responses under accurately simulated conditions via microfabrication, microelectronics and microfluidics.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The development of organ chips has enabled the study of the complex pathophysiology of human viral infections.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] An example is the liver chip platform that has enabled studies of viral hepatitis.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Recent work has highlighted the use of organ-on-a-chip systems for modelling aging processes and age-related diseases, including neurodegeneration, cardiovascular dysfunction, and skin aging.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] A lab-on-a-chip is a device that integrates one or several laboratory functions on a single chip that deals with handling particles in hollow microfluidic channels.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] It has been developed for over a decade.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Advantages in handling particles at such a small scale include lowering fluid volume consumption (lower reagents costs, less waste), increasing portability of the devices, increasing process control (due to quicker thermo-chemical reactions) and decreasing fabrication costs.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Additionally, microfluidic flow is entirely laminar (i.e., no turbulence).
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Consequently, there is virtually no mixing between neighboring streams in one hollow channel.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In cellular biology convergence, this rare property in fluids has been leveraged to better study complex cell behaviors, such as cell motility in response to chemotactic stimuli, stem cell differentiation, axon guidance, subcellular propagation of biochemical signaling and embryonic development.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] 3D cell-culture models exceed 2D culture systems by promoting higher levels of cell differentiation and tissue organization.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] 3D culture systems are more successful because the flexibility of the ECM gels accommodates shape changes and cell-cell connections – formerly prohibited by rigid 2D culture substrates.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The most widely used 3D cell culture models include spheroids and organoids.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The application of microfluidics in organs-on-chips enables the efficient transport and distribution of nutrients and other soluble cues throughout the viable 3D tissue constructs.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Organs-on-chips are referred to as the next wave of 3D cell-culture models that mimic whole living organs' biological activities, dynamic mechanical properties and biochemical functionalities.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Brain-on-a-chip devices can span multiple levels of complexity in terms of cell culture methodology and can include brain parenchyma and/or blood-brain barrier tissues.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Devices have been made using platforms that range from traditional 2D cell culture to 3D tissues in the form of organotypic brain slices and more recently organoids.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Organotypic brain slices are an *in vitro* model that replicates *in vivo* physiology with additional throughput and optical benefits, thus pairing well with microfluidic devices.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Brain slices have advantages over primary cell culture in that tissue architecture is preserved and multicellular interactions can still occur.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] There is flexibility in their use, as slices can be used acutely (less than 6 hours after slice harvesting) or cultured for later experimental use.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Because organotypic brain slices can maintain viability for weeks, they allow for long-term effects to be studied.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Slice-based systems also provide experimental access with precise control of extracellular environments, making it a suitable platform for correlating disease with neuropathological outcomes.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Organotypic brain slices can be extracted and cultured from multiple animal species (e.g. rats), but also from humans.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Microfluidic devices have been paired with organotypic slices to improve culture viability.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The standard procedure for culturing organotypic brain slices (around 300 microns in thickness) uses semi-porous membranes to create an air-medium interface, but this technique results in diffusion limitations of nutrients and dissolved gases.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Because microfluidic systems introduce laminar flow of these necessary nutrients and gases, transport is improved and higher tissue viability can be achieved.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In addition to keeping standard slices viable, brain-on-a-chip platforms have allowed the successful culturing of thicker brain slices (approximately 700 microns), despite a significant transport barrier due to thickness.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] As thicker slices retain more native tissue architecture, this allows brain-on-a-chip devices to achieve more "*in vivo*-like" characteristics without sacrificing cell viability.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Microfluidic devices support high-throughput screening and toxicological assessments in both 2D and slice cultures, leading to the development of novel therapeutics targeted for the brain.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] One device was able to screen the drugs pitavastatin and irinotecan combinatorically in glioblastoma multiform (the most common form of human brain cancer).
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] These screening approaches have been combined with the modeling of the blood-brain barrier (BBB), a significant hurdle for drugs to overcome when treating the brain, allowing for drug efficacy across this barrier to be studied *in vitro*.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Microfluidic probes have been used to deliver dyes with high regional precision, making way for localized microperfusion in drug applications.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Because microfluidic devices can be designed with optical accessibility, this also allows for the visualization of morphology and processes in specific regions or individual cells.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Brain-on-a-chip systems can model organ-level physiology in neurological diseases, such as Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, and multiple sclerosis more accurately than with traditional 2D and 3D cell culture techniques.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The ability to model these diseases in a way that is indicative of *in vivo* conditions is essential for the translation of therapies and treatments.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Additionally, brain-on-a-chip devices have been used for medical diagnostics, such as in biomarker detection for cancer in brain tissue slices.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Brain-on-a-chip devices can cause shear stress on cells or tissue due to flow through small channels, which can result in cellular damage.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] These small channels also introduce susceptibility to the trapping of air bubbles that can disrupt flow and potentially cause damage to the cells.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The widespread use of PDMS (polydimethylsiloxane) in brain-on-a-chip devices has some drawbacks.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Although PDMS is cheap, malleable, and transparent, proteins and small molecules can be absorbed by it and later leech at uncontrolled rates.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Despite the progress in microfluidic BBB devices, these devices are often too technically complex, require highly specialized setups and equipment, and are unable to detect temporal and spatial differences in the transport kinetics of substances that migrate across cellular barriers.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Also, direct measurements of permeability in these models are limited due to the limited perfusion and complex, poorly defined geometry of the newly formed microvascular network.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The human gut-on-a-chip contains two microchannels that are separated by the flexible porous Extracellular Matrix (ECM)-coated membrane lined by the gut epithelial cells: Caco-2, which has been used extensively as the intestinal barrier.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Caco-2 cells are cultured under spontaneous differentiation of its parental cell, a human colon adenocarcinoma, that represent the model of protective and absorptive properties of the gut.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The microchannels are fabricated from polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS) polymer.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In order to mimic the gut microenvironment, peristalsis-like fluid flow is designed.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] By inducing suction in the vacuum chambers along both sides of the main cell channel bilayer, cyclic mechanical strain of stretching and relaxing are developed to mimic the gut behaviors.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Furthermore, cells undergo spontaneous villus morphogenesis and differentiation, which generalizes characteristics of intestinal cells.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Under the three-dimensional villi scaffold, cells not only proliferate, but metabolic activities are also enhanced.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Another important player in the gut is the microbes, namely gut microbiota.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Many microbial species in the gut microbiota are strict anaerobes.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In order to co-culture these oxygen intolerant anaerobes with the oxygen favorable intestinal cells, a polysulfone fabricated gut-on-a-chip is designed.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The system maintained the co-culture of colon epithelial cells, goblet-like cells, and bacteria *Faecalibacterium prausnitzii*, *Eubacterium rectale*, and *Bacteroides thetaiotaomicron*.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Oral administration is one of the most common methods for drug administration.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] It allows patients, especially out-patients, to self-serve the drugs with minimal possibility of experiencing acute drug reactions and in most cases: pain-free.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] However, the drug's action in the body can be largely influenced by the first pass effect.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The gut, which plays an important role in the human digestive system, determines the effectiveness of a drug by absorbing its chemical and biological properties selectively.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] While it is costly and time-consuming to develop new drugs, the fact that the gut-on-a-chip technology attains a high level of throughput has significantly decreased research and development costs and time for new drugs.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Even though the cause for inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) is elusive, its pathophysiology involves the gut microbiota.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Current methods of inducing IBD are using inflammatory cues to activate Caco-2.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] It was found that the intestinal epithelium experienced a reduction in barrier function and increased cytokine concentrations.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The gut-on-a-chip allowed for the assessment on drug transport, absorption and toxicity as well as potential developments in studying pathogenesis and interactions in the microenvironment overall.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Immune cells are essential in mediating inflammatory processes in many gastrointestinal disorders, a recent gut-on-a-chip system also includes multiple immune cells, e.g., macrophages, dendritic cells, and CD4+ T cells in the system.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Additionally, the gut-on-a-chip allows the testing of anti-inflammatory effects of bacterial species.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The chip was used to model human radiation-induced injury to the intestine in vitro as it recapitulated the injuries at both cellular and tissue levels.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Injuries include but not limited to: inhabitation of mucus production, promotion of villus blunting, and distortion of microvilli.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Lung-on-a-chips are being designed in an effort to improve the physiological relevance of existing in vitro alveolar-capillary interface models.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Such a multifunctional microdevice can reproduce key structural, functional and mechanical properties of the human alveolar-capillary interface (i.e., the fundamental functional unit of the living lung).
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Dongeun Huh from Wyss Institute for Biologically Inspired Engineering at Harvard describes their fabrication of a system containing two closely apposed microchannels separated by a thin (10 μm) porous flexible membrane made of PDMS.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The device largely comprises three microfluidic channels, and only the middle one holds the porous membrane.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Culture cells were grown on either side of the membrane: human alveolar epithelial cells on one side, and human pulmonary microvascular endothelial cells on the other.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The compartmentalization of the channels facilitates not only the flow of air as a fluid which delivers cells and nutrients to the apical surface of the epithelium, but also allows for pressure differences to exist between the middle and side channels.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] During normal inspiration in a human's respiratory cycle, intrapleural pressure decreases, triggering an expansion of the alveoli.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] As air is pulled into the lungs, alveolar epithelium and the coupled endothelium in the capillaries are stretched.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Since a vacuum is connected to the side channels, a decrease in pressure will cause the middle channel to expand, thus stretching the porous membrane and subsequently, the entire alveolar-capillary interface.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In order to fully validate the biological accuracy of a device, its whole-organ responses must be evaluated.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Additionally, researchers believe the potential value of this lung-on-a-chip system will aid in toxicology applications.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] By investigating the pulmonary response to nanoparticles, researchers hope to learn more about health risks in certain environments, and correct previously oversimplified in vitro models.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Because a microfluidic lung-on-a-chip can more exactly reproduce the mechanical properties of a living human lung, its physiological responses will be quicker and more accurate than a Transwell culture system.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Nevertheless, published studies admit that responses of a lung-on-a-chip do not yet fully reproduce the responses of native alveolar epithelial cells.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Past efforts to replicate in vivo cardiac tissue environments have proven to be challenging due to difficulties when mimicking contractility and electrophysiological responses.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Such features would greatly increase the accuracy of in vitro experiments.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Microfluidics has already contributed to in vitro experiments on cardiomyocytes, which generate the electrical impulses that control the heart rate.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] For instance, researchers have built an array of PDMS microchambers, aligned with sensors and stimulating electrodes as a tool that will electrochemically and optically monitor the cardiomyocytes' metabolism.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Another lab-on-a-chip similarly combined a microfluidic network in PDMS with planar microelectrodes, this time to measure extracellular potentials from single adult murine cardiomyocytes.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] This heart-on-a-chip is a biohybrid construct: an engineered anisotropic ventricular myocardium is an elastomeric thin film.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The design and fabrication process of this particular microfluidic device entails first covering the edges of a glass surface with tape (or any protective film) such as to contour the substrate's desired shape.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] A spin coat layer of PNIPA is then applied.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] After its dissolution, the protective film is peeled away, resulting in a self-standing body of PNIPA.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The final steps involve the spin coating of protective surface of PDMS over the cover slip and curing.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Muscular thin films (MTF) enable cardiac muscle monolayers to be engineered on a thin flexible substrate of PDMS.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In order to properly seed the 2D cell culture, a microcontact printing technique was used to lay out a fibronectin "brick wall" pattern on the PDMS surface.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Once the ventricular myocytes were seeded on the functionalized substrate, the fibronectin pattern oriented them to generate an anisotropic monolayer.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] After the cutting of the thin films into two rows with rectangular teeth, and subsequent placement of the whole device in a bath, electrodes stimulate the contraction of the myocytes via a field-stimulation – thus curving the strips/teeth in the MTF.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] While researchers have focused on 2D cell cultures, 3D cell constructs mimic the *in vivo* environment and the interactions (e.g., cell to cell) occurring in the human body better.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Hence, they are considered promising models for studies such as toxicology and response to drugs.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Based on the study of Chen et al., the interactions of valvular endothelial/interstitial cells (VECs/VICs) are studied via a 3D PDMS-glass microfluidic device with a top channel flowed with VECs under shear stress, a membrane with uniform pores, and a bottom channel containing VIC-hydrogel.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] VECs are verified to restrain the differentiation of morbid VIC myofibroblast, with reinforced suppression by shear stress.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Another PDMS 3D microfluidic heart-on-a-chip design is measured to generate 10% to 15% of uniaxial cyclic mechanical strains.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The device consists of a cell culture with hanging posts for caging and an actuation compartment with scaffolding posts to avoid buckling of PDMS, along with the cardiac cycle pressure signal imitation.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The neonatal rat micro-engineered cardiac tissues (μECTs) stimulated by this design show improved synchronous beating, proliferation, maturation, and viability compared to the unstimulated control.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The contraction rate of human induced pluripotent stem cell-derived cardiomyocytes (hiPSC-CM) is observed to accelerate with 100-fold less isoprenaline, a heart block treatment, when having electrical pacing signal (+ES) compared to that without ES.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] 3D microfluidic heart-on-a-chips have also facilitated the research of heart diseases.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] For instance, cardiac hypertrophy and fibrosis are studied via the respective biomarker level of the mechanically stimulated μECTs, such as atrial natriuretic peptide (ANP) for the former and transforming growth factor-β (TGF-β) for the latter.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Also, the knowledge of ischaemia is gained by action potential observations.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The microfluidic approaches utilized for teasing apart specific mechanisms at the single-cell level and at the tissue-level are becoming increasingly sophisticated and so are the fabrication methods.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Rapid dissemination and availability of low cost, high resolution 3D printing technology is revolutionizing this space and opening new possibilities for building patient specific heart and cardiovascular systems.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The confluence of high resolution 3D printing, patient derived iPSCs with artificial intelligence is posed to make significant strides towards truly personalized heart modelling and ultimately, patient care.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Renal cells and nephrons have already been simulated by microfluidic devices.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] "Such cell cultures can lead to new insights into cell and organ function and be used for drug screening".
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] A kidney-on-a-chip device has the potential to accelerate research encompassing artificial replacement for lost kidney function.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Nowadays, dialysis requires patients to go to a clinic up to three times per week.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] A more transportable and accessible form of treatment would not only increase the patient's overall health (by increasing frequency of treatment), but the whole process would become more efficient and tolerable.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Artificial kidney research is striving to bring transportability, wearability and perhaps implantation capability to the devices through innovative disciplines: microfluidics, miniaturization and nanotechnology.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The nephron is the functional unit of the kidney and is composed of a glomerulus and a tubular component.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Researchers at MIT claim to have designed a bioartificial device that replicates the function of the nephron's glomerulus, proximal convoluted tubule and loop of Henle.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Each part of the device has its unique design, generally consisting of two microfabricated layers separated by a membrane.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The only inlet to the microfluidic device is designed for the entering blood sample.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In the glomerulus' section of the nephron, the membrane allows certain blood particles through its wall of capillary cells, composed by the endothelium, basement membrane and the epithelial podocytes.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The fluid that is filtered from the capillary blood into Bowman's space is called filtrate or primary urine.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In the tubules, some substances are added to the filtrate as part of the urine formation, and some substances reabsorbed out of the filtrate and back into the blood.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The first segment of these tubules is the proximal convoluted tubule.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] This is where the almost complete absorption of nutritionally important substances takes place.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In the device, this section is merely a straight channel, but blood particles going to the filtrate have to cross the previously mentioned membrane and a layer of renal proximal tubule cells.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The second segment of the tubules is the loop of Henle where the reabsorption of water and ions from the urine takes place.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The device's looping channels strives to simulate the countercurrent mechanism of the loop of Henle.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Likewise, the loop of Henle requires a number of different cell types because each cell type has distinct transport properties and characteristics.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] These include the descending limb cells, thin ascending limb cells, thick ascending limb cells, cortical collecting duct cells and medullary collecting duct cells.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] For example, the large majority of passive transport of water occurs in the proximal tubule and the descending thin limb, or the active transport of NaCl largely occurs in the proximal tubule and the thick ascending limb.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] One recent report illustrates a biomimic nephron on hydrogel microfluidic devices with establishing the function of passive diffusion.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The complex physiological function of nephron is achieved on the basis of interactions between vessels and tubules (both are hollow channels).
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] However, conventional laboratory techniques usually focus on 2D structures, such as petri-dish that lacks capability to recapitulate real physiology that occurs in 3D.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Therefore, the authors developed a new method to fabricate functional, cell-lining and perfusable microchannels inside 3D hydrogel.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The vessel endothelial and renal epithelial cells are cultured inside hydrogel microchannel and form cellular coverage to mimic vessels and tubules, respectively.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] They employed confocal microscope to examine the passive diffusion of one small organic molecule (usually drugs) between the vessels and tubules in hydrogel.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The study demonstrates the beneficial potential to mimic renal physiology for regenerative medicine and drug screening.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The liver is a major organ of metabolism, and it is related to glycogen storage, decomposition of red blood cells, certain protein and hormone synthesis, and detoxification.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Within these functions, its detoxification response is essential for new drug development and clinical trials.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In addition, because of its multi-functions, the liver is prone to many diseases, and liver diseases have become a global challenge.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Liver-on-a-chip devices utilize microfluidic techniques to simulate the hepatic system by imitating complex hepatic lobules that involve liver functions.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Liver-on-a-chip devices provide a good model to help researchers work on dysfunction and pathogenesis of the liver with relatively low cost.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Researchers use primary rat hepatocytes and other nonparenchymal cells.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] This coculture method is extensively studied and is proved to be beneficial for extension of hepatocytes survival time and support the performance of liver-specific functions.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Many liver-on-a-chip systems are made of poly(dimethylsiloxane) (PDMS) with multiple channels and chambers based on specific design and objective.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] PDMS is used and has become popular because it has relatively low price for raw materials, and it is also easily molded for microfluidic devices.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] But PDMS can absorb important signaling molecules including proteins and hormones.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Other more inert materials such as polysulfone or polycarbonate are used in liver-chips.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] A study by Emulate researchers assessed advantages of using liver-chips predicting drug-induced liver injury which could reduce the high costs and time needed in drug development workflows/pipelines, sometimes described as the pharmaceutical industry's "productivity crisis".
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Zaher Nahle subsequently outlined 12 "reasons why micro-physiological systems (MPS) like organ-chips are better at modeling human diseases".
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] One design from Kane et al. cocultures primary rat hepatocytes and 3T3-J2 fibroblasts in an 8*8 element array of microfluidic wells.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Each well is separated into two chambers.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The primary chamber contains rat hepatocytes and 3T3-J2 fibroblasts and is made of glass for cells adhesion.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Each of primary chamber is connected to a microfluidic network that supply metabolic substrate and remove metabolic byproducts.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] A 100 μm thick membrane of PDMS separates the primary and secondary chamber, allowing the secondary chamber to be connected to another microfluidic network that perfuses 37 °C room air with 10% carbon dioxide, and producing air exchange for rat hepatocytes.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The production of urea and steady-state protein proves the viability of this device for use in high-throughput toxicity studies.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Another design from Kang et al. cocultures primary rat hepatocytes and endothelial cells.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Hepatocytes and endothelial cells are then planted on the device and are separated by a thin Matrigel layer in between.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The metabolic substrate and metabolic byproducts share this channel to be supplied or removed.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Later, a dual-channel is made, and endothelial cells and hepatocytes cells have their own channels to supply the substrate or remove the byproduct.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The production of urea and positive result on hepatitis B virus (HBV) replication test shows its potential to study hepatotropic viruses.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] There are a few other applications on liver-on-a-chip.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Lu et al. developed a liver tumor-on-a-chip model.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The decellularized liver matrix (DLM)-gelatin methacryloyl (GelMA)-based biomimetic liver tumor-on-a-chip proved to be a suitable design for further anti-tumor studies.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Zhou et al. analyzed alcohol injures on the hepatocytes and the signaling and recovery.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] It has also been possible to develop co-culture chips that can be used to study metabolic interactions.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The liver-on-a-chip has shown its great potential for liver-related research.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Future goals for liver-on-a-chip devices focus on recapitulating a more realistic hepatic environment, including reagents in fluids, cell types, extending survival time, etc.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Recreation of the prostate epithelium is motivated by evidence suggesting it to be the site of nucleation in cancer metastasis.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] These systems essentially serve as the next step in the development of cells cultured from mice to two and subsequently three-dimensional human cell culturing.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] PDMS developments have enabled the creation of microfluidic systems that offer the benefit of adjustable topography, gas and liquid exchange, as well as an ease of observation via conventional microscopy.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Researchers at the University of Grenoble Alpes have outlined a methodology that utilizes such a microfluidic system in the attempt to construct a viable Prostate epithelium model.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The approach focuses on a cylindrical microchannel configuration, mimicking the morphology of a human secretory duct, within which the epithelium is located.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Various microchannel diameters were assessed for successful promotion of cell cultures, and it was observed that diameters of 150-400 μm were the most successful.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Furthermore, cellular adhesion endured throughout this experimentation, despite the introduction of physical stress through variations in microfluidic currents.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The objective of these constructions is to facilitate the collection of prostatic fluid, along with gauging cellular reactions to microenvironmental changes.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Additionally, prostate-on-a-chip enables the recreation of metastasis scenarios, which allows the assessment of drug candidates and other therapeutic approaches.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Scalability of this method is also attractive to researchers, as the reusable mold approach ensures a low-cost of production.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Cardiovascular diseases are often caused by changes in structure and function of small blood vessels.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] For instance, self-reported rates of hypertension suggest that the rate is increasing, says a 2003 report from the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Axel Gunther from the University of Toronto argues that such MEMS-based devices could potentially help in the assessment of a patient's microvascular status in a clinical setting (personalized medicine).
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Conventional methods used to examine intrinsic properties of isolated resistance vessels (arterioles and small arteries with diameters varying between 30 μm and 300 μm) include the pressure myography technique.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] However, such methods currently require manually skilled personnel and are not scalable.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] An artery-on-a-chip could overcome several of these limitations by accommodating an artery onto a platform which would be scalable, inexpensive and possibly automated in its manufacturing.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] An organ-based microfluidic platform has been developed as a lab-on-a-chip onto which a fragile blood vessel can be fixed, allowing for determinants of resistance artery malfunctions to be studied.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The artery microenvironment is characterized by surrounding temperature, transmural pressure, and luminal & abluminal drug concentrations.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The multiple inputs from a microenvironment cause a wide range of mechanical or chemical stimuli on the smooth muscle cells (SMCs) and endothelial cells (ECs) that line the vessel's outer and luminal walls, respectively.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Endothelial cells are responsible for releasing vasoconstriction and vasodilator factors, thus modifying tone.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Vascular tone is defined as the degree of constriction inside a blood vessel relative to its maximum diameter.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Pathogenic concepts currently believe that subtle changes to this microenvironment have pronounced effects on arterial tone and can severely alter peripheral vascular resistance.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The engineers behind this design believe that a specific strength lies in its ability to control and simulate heterogeneous spatiotemporal influences found within the microenvironment, whereas myography protocols have, by virtue of their design, only established homogeneous microenvironments.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] They proved that by delivering phenylephrine through only one of the two channels providing superfusion to the outer walls, the drug-facing side constricted much more than the drug opposing side.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The artery-on-a-chip is designed for reversible implantation of the sample.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The device contains a microchannel network, an artery loading area and a separate artery inspection area.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] There is a microchannel used for loading the artery segment, and when the loading well is sealed, it is also used as a perfusion channel, to replicate the process of nutritive delivery of arterial blood to a capillary bed in the biological tissue.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Another pair of microchannels serves to fix the two ends of the arterial segment.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Finally, the last pair of microchannels is used to provide superfusion flow rates, in order to maintain the physiological and metabolic activity of the organ by delivering a constant sustaining medium over the abluminal wall.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] A thermoelectric heater and a thermoresistor are connected to the chip and maintain physiological temperatures at the artery inspection area.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The protocol of loading and securing the tissue sample into the inspection zone helps understand how this approach acknowledges whole organ functions.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] After immersing the tissue segment into the loading well, the loading process is driven by a syringe withdrawing a constant flow rate of buffer solution at the far end of the loading channel.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] This causes the transport of the artery towards its dedicated position.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] This is done with closed fixation and superfusion in/outlet lines.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] After stopping the pump, sub-atmospheric pressure is applied through one of the fixation channels.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Then after sealing the loading well shut, the second fixation channel is subjected to a sub-atmospheric pressure.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Now the artery is symmetrically established in the inspection area, and a transmural pressure is felt by the segment.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The remaining channels are opened and constant perfusion and superfusion are adjusted using separate syringe pumps.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Vessel-on-chips have been applied to study many disease processes.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] For example, Alireza Mashaghi and his co-workers developed a model to study viral hemorrhagic syndrome, which involves virus induced vascular integrity loss.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The model was used to study Ebola virus disease and to study anti-Ebola drugs.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In 2021, the approach has been adapted to model Lassa fever and to show the therapeutic effects of peptide FX-06 for Lassa virus disease.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Human skin is the first line of defense against many pathogens and can itself be subject to a variety of diseases and issues, such as cancers and inflammation.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Despite the wide variety of potential applications, relatively little research has gone into developing a skin-on-a-chip compared to many other organ-on-a-chips, such as lungs and kidneys.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] One additional difficulty is the variability of cell-culture scaffolding, or the base substance in which to culture cells, that is used in skin-on-chip devices.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In the human body, this substance is known as the extracellular matrix.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The extracellular matrix (ECM) is composed primarily of collagen, and various collagen-based scaffolding has been tested in SoC models.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Collagen tends to detach from the microfluidic backbone during culturing due to the contraction of fibroblasts.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] One study attempted to address this problem by comparing the qualities of collagen scaffolding from three different animal sources: pig skin, rat tail, and duck feet.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Other studies also faced detachment issues due to contraction, which can problematic considering that the process of full skin differentiation can take up to several weeks.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Contraction issues have been avoided by replacing collagen scaffolding with a fibrin-based dermal matrix, which did not contract.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] This improved differentiation and growth is thought to be in part a product of shear stress created by the pressure gradient along a microchannel due to fluid flow, which may also improve nutrient supply to cells not directly adjacent to the medium.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In static cultures, used in traditional skin equivalents, cells receive nutrients in the medium only through diffusion, whereas dynamic perfusion can improve nutrient flow through interstitial spaces, or gaps between cells.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] This perfusion has also been demonstrated to improve tight junction formation of the *stratum corneum*, the tough outer layer of the epidermis, which is the main barrier to penetration of the surface layer of the skin.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Dynamic perfusion may also improve cell viability, demonstrated by placing a commercial skin equivalent in a microfluidic platform that extended the expected lifespan by several weeks.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] This early study also demonstrated the importance of hair follicles in skin equivalent models.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Hair follicles are the primary route into the subcutaneous layer for topical creams and other substances applied to the surface of the skin, a feature that more recent studies have often not accounted for.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] One study developed a SoC consisting of three layers, the epidermis, dermis, and endothelial layer, separated by porous membranes, to study edema, swelling due to extracellular fluid accumulation, a common response to infection or injury and an essential step for cellular repair.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] It was demonstrated that pre-application of Dex, a steroidal cream with anti-inflammatory properties, reduced this swelling in the SoC.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The endometrium has been modeled for its role in implantation and other stages of pregnancy.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Researchers are working towards building a multi-channel 3D microfluidic cell culture system that compartmentalizes microenvironments in which 3D cellular aggregates are cultured to mimic multiple organs in the body.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Most organ-on-a-chip models today only culture one cell type, so even though they may be valid models for studying whole organ functions, the systemic effect of a drug on the human body is not verified.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In particular, an integrated cell culture analog (μCCA) was developed and included lung cells, drug-metabolizing liver and fat cells.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The cells were linked in a 2D fluidic network with culture medium circulating as a blood surrogate, thus efficiently providing a nutritional delivery transport system, while simultaneously removing wastes from the cells.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] "The development of the μCCA laid the foundation for a realistic in vitro pharmacokinetic model and provided an integrated biomimetic system for culturing multiple cell types with high fidelity to in vivo situations", claim C.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] They have developed a microfluidic human-on-a-chip, culturing four different cell types to mimic four human organs: liver, lung, kidney and fat.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] They focused on developing a standard serum-free culture media that would be valuable to all cell types included in the device.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Optimized standard media are generally targeted to one specific cell-type, whereas a human-on-a-chip will evidently require a common medium (CM).
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] In fact, they claim to have identified a cell culture CM that, when used to perfuse all cell cultures in the microfluidic device, maintains the cells' functional levels.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Heightening the sensitivity of the in vitro cultured cells ensures the validity of the device, or that any drug injected into the microchannels will stimulate an identical physiological and metabolic reaction from the sample cells as whole organs in humans.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] A human-on-a-chip design that allows tuning microfluidic transport to multiple tissues using a single fluidic actuator was designed and evaluated for modelling prediabetic hyperglycaemia using liver and pancreatic tissues.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] With more extensive development of these kinds of chips, pharmaceutical companies will potentially be able to measure direct effects of one organ's reaction on another.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] For instance, the delivery of biochemical substances would be screened to confirm that even though it may benefit one cell type, it does not compromise the functions of others.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] It is probably already possible to print these organs with 3D printers, but the cost is too high.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Designing whole body biomimetic devices addresses a major reservation that pharmaceutical companies have towards organs-on-chips, namely the isolation of organs.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] As these devices become more and more accessible, the complexity of the design increases exponentially.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] Systems will soon have to simultaneously provide mechanical perturbation and fluid flow through a circulatory system.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] "Anything that requires dynamic control rather than just static control is a challenge", says Takayama from the University of Michigan.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] This challenge has been partially tackled by tissue engineering Linda Griffith group from MIT.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] A complex multi-organ-on-a-chip was developed to have 4, 7, or 10 organs interconnected through fluidic control.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p01] The system is able to maintain the function of these organs for weeks.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] In the early phase of drug development, animal models were the only way of obtaining in vivo data that would predict the human pharmacokinetic responses.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] However, experiments on animals are lengthy, expensive and controversial.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] For example, animal models are often subjected to mechanical or chemical techniques that simulate human injuries.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] There are also concerns with regards to the validity of such animal models, due to deficiency in cross-species extrapolation.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Moreover, animal models offer very limited control of individual variables and it can be cumbersome to harvest specific information.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) announced its intent in April 2025 to phase out mandatory animal testing requirements for certain drug classes, signalling a broader regulatory acceptance of new approach methodologies.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] These methodologies range from microphysiological systems, also known as organ-on-a-chip, to artificial intelligence (AI)-based modelling with intention to accelerate preclinical development.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Therefore, mimicking a human's physiological responses in an in vitro model needs to be made more affordable, and needs to offer cellular level control in biological experiments: biomimetic microfluidic systems could replace animal testing.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] The development of MEMS-based biochips that reproduce complex organ-level pathological responses could revolutionize many fields, including toxicology and the developmental process of pharmaceuticals and cosmetics that rely on animal testing and clinical trials.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Recently, physiologically based perfusion in vitro systems have been developed to provide cell culture environment close to in vivo cell environment.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] A new testing platforms based on multi-compartmental perfused systems have gained a remarkable interest in pharmacology and toxicology.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] It aims to provide a cell culture environment close to the in vivo situation to reproduce more reliably *in vivo* mechanisms or ADME processes that involve its absorption, distribution, metabolism, and elimination.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Perfused in vitro systems combined with kinetic modelling are promising tools for studying in vitro the different processes involved in the toxicokinetics of xenobiotics.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Some emerging technologies have the ability to measure multiple biological processes in a co-culture of mixed cell types, cells from different parts of the body, which is suggested to provide more similarity to in Vivo models.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Mathematical pharmacokinetic (PK) models aim to estimate concentration-time profiles within each organ on the basis of the initial drug dose.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Such mathematical models can be relatively simple, treating the body as a single compartment in which the drug distribution reaches a rapid equilibrium after administration.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Mathematical models can be highly accurate when all parameters involved are known.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Models that combine PK or PBPK models with PD models can predict the time-dependent pharmacological effects of a drug.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] We can nowadays predict with PBPK models the PK of about any chemical in humans, almost from first principles.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] These models can be either very simple, like statistical dose-response models, or sophisticated and based on systems biology, according to the goal pursued and the data available.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] All we need for those models are good parameter values for the molecule of interest.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Microfluidic cell culture systems such as micro cell culture analogs (μCCAs) could be used in conjunction with PBPK models.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] These μCCAs scaled-down devices, termed also body-on-a-chip devices, can simulate multi-tissue interactions under near-physiological fluid flow conditions and with realistic tissue-to-tissue size ratios .
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Data obtained with these systems may be used to test and refine mechanistic hypotheses.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Microfabricating devices also allows us to custom-design them and scale the organs' compartments correctly with respect to one another.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Because the device can be used with both animal and human cells, it can facilitate cross-species extrapolation.
[src:organoids/organ-on-a-chip-p02] Used in conjunction with PBPK models, the devices permit an estimation of effective concentrations that can be used for studies with animal models or predict the human response.
[src:organoids/organoid] An **organoid** is a miniaturised and simplified version of an organ produced *in vitro* in three dimensions that mimics the key functional, structural, and biological complexity of that organ.
[src:organoids/organoid] It is derived from one or a few cells from a tissue, embryonic stem cells, or induced pluripotent stem cells, which can self-organize in three-dimensional culture owing to their self-renewal and differentiation capacities.
[src:organoids/organoid] The technique for growing organoids has rapidly improved since the early 2010s, and *The Scientist* named it one of the biggest scientific advancements of 2013.
[src:organoids/organoid] Scientists and engineers use organoids to study development and disease in the laboratory, for drug discovery and development in industry, personalized diagnostics and medicine, gene and cell therapies, tissue engineering, and regenerative medicine.
[src:organoids/organoid] Attempts to create organs *in vitro* started in 1907 with one of the first dissociation-reaggregation experiments where Henry Van Peters Wilson demonstrated that mechanically dissociated sponge cells can reaggregate and self-organize to generate a whole organism.
[src:organoids/organoid] In the subsequent decades, multiple labs were able to generate different types of organs *in vitro* through the dissociation and reaggregation of organ tissues obtained from amphibians and embryonic chicks.
[src:organoids/organoid] The formation of first tissue-like colonies *in vitro* was observed for the first time by co-culturing keratinocytes and 3T3 fibroblasts.
[src:organoids/organoid] The phenomena of mechanically dissociated cells aggregating and reorganizing to reform the tissue they were obtained from subsequently led to the development of the differential adhesion hypothesis by Malcolm Steinberg in 1964.
[src:organoids/organoid] The advent of the field of organoids started with a shift from culturing and differentiating stem cells in two dimensional (2D) media, to three dimensional (3D) media to allow for the development of the complex 3-dimensional structures of organs.
[src:organoids/organoid] Utilization of 3D media culture media methods for the structural organization was made possible with the development of extracellular matrices (ECM).
[src:organoids/organoid] In the late 1980s, Bissell and colleagues showed that a laminin rich gel can be used as a basement membrane for differentiation and morphogenesis in cell cultures of mammary epithelial cells.
[src:organoids/organoid] Since 1987, researchers have devised different methods for 3D culturing, and were able to utilize different types of stem cells to generate organoids resembling a multitude of organs.
[src:organoids/organoid] In the 1990s, in addition to their role in physical support, the role of ECM components in gene expression by their interaction with integrin-based focal adhesion pathways was reported.
[src:organoids/organoid] In 1998 scientists first isolated stem cells from human blastocysts and cultured them, while the reprogramming of mouse and human fibroblasts to generate Induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSC) was introduced later and greatly enhanced stem cell and organoid research.
[src:organoids/organoid] In 2006, Yaakov Nahmias and David Odde showed the self-assembly of vascular liver organoid maintained for over 50 days *in vitro*.
[src:organoids/organoid] In 2008, Yoshiki Sasai and his team at RIKEN institute demonstrated that stem cells can be coaxed into balls of neural cells that self-organize into distinctive layers.
[src:organoids/organoid] In 2009 the Laboratory of Hans Clevers at Hubrecht Institute and University Medical Center Utrecht, Netherlands, showed that single LGR5-expressing intestinal stem cells self-organize to crypt-villus structures *in vitro* without necessity of a mesenchymal niche, making them the first organoids.
[src:organoids/organoid] Davies demonstrated the production of renal organoids from murine fetus-derived renogenic stem cells.
[src:organoids/organoid] Subsequent reports showed significant physiological function of these organoids *in vitro* and *in vivo*.
[src:organoids/organoid] Meritxell Huch and Craig Dorrell at Hubrecht Institute and University Medical Center Utrecht demonstrated that single Lgr5+ cells from damaged mouse liver can be clonally expanded as liver organoids in Rspo1-based culture medium over several months.
[src:organoids/organoid] In 2014, Artem Shkumatov et al. at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign demonstrated that cardiovascular organoids can be formed from ES cells through modulation of the substrate stiffness, to which they adhere.
[src:organoids/organoid] Physiological stiffness promoted three-dimensionality of EBs and cardiomyogenic differentiation.
[src:organoids/organoid] Organoid formation generally requires culturing the stem cells or progenitor cells in a 3D medium.
[src:organoids/organoid] Stem cells have the ability to self-renew and differentiate into various cell subtypes, and they enable understanding the processes of development and disease progression.
[src:organoids/organoid] Therefore organoids derived from stem cells enable studying biology and physiology at the organ level.
[src:organoids/organoid] The 3D medium can be made using an extracellular matrix hydrogel such as Matrigel or Cultrex BME, which is a laminin-rich extracellular matrix that is secreted by the Engelbreth-Holm-Swarm tumor line.
[src:organoids/organoid] Organoid bodies can then be made through embedding stem cells in the 3D medium.
[src:organoids/organoid] When pluripotent stem cells are used for the creation of the organoid, the cells are usually, but not all the time, allowed to form embryoid bodies.
[src:organoids/organoid] Those embryoid bodies are then pharmacologically treated with patterning factors to drive the formation of the desired organoid identity.
[src:organoids/organoid] Organoids have also been created using adult stem cells extracted from the target organ, and cultured in 3D media.
[src:organoids/organoid] Biochemical cues have been incorporated in 3D organoid cultures and with exposure of morphogenes, morphogen inhibitors, or growth factors, organoid models can be developed using embryonic stem cells (ESCs) or adult stem cells (ASCs).
[src:organoids/organoid] Vascularization techniques can be utilized to embody microenvironments that are close to their counterparts, physiologically.
[src:organoids/organoid] Vasculature systems that can facilitate oxygen or nutrients to the inner mass of organoids can be achieved through microfluidic systems, vascular endothelial growth factor delivery systems, and endothelial cell-coated modules.
[src:organoids/organoid] With patient-derived induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) and CRISPR/Cas-based genome editing technologies, genome-edited or mutated pluripotent stem cells (PSCs) with altered signaling cues can be generated to control intrinsic cues within organoids.
[src:organoids/organoid] A multitude of organ structures have been recapitulated using organoids.
[src:organoids/organoid] This section aims to outline the state of the field as of now through providing an abridged list of the organoids that have been successfully created, along with a brief outline based on the most recent literature for each organoid, and examples of how it has been utilized in research.
[src:organoids/organoid] A cerebral organoid describes artificially grown, *in vitro*, miniature organs resembling the brain.
[src:organoids/organoid] Cerebral organoids are created by culturing human pluripotent stem cells in a three-dimensional structure using rotational bioreactor and develop over the course of months.
[src:organoids/organoid] The procedure has potential applications in the study of brain development, physiology and function.
[src:organoids/organoid] Cerebral organoids may experience "simple sensations" in response to external stimulation and neuroscientists are among those expressing concern that such organs could develop sentience.
[src:organoids/organoid] They propose that further evolution of the technique needs to be subject to a rigorous oversight procedure.
[src:organoids/organoid] In 2023, researchers have built a hybrid biocomputer that combines laboratory-grown human brain organoids with conventional circuits, and can complete tasks such as voice recognition.
[src:organoids/organoid] Cerebral Organoids are currently being used to research and develop Organoid Intelligence (OI) technologies.
[src:organoids/organoid] Gastrointestinal organoids refer to organoids that recapitulate structures of the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:organoids/organoid] Intestinal organoids have thus far been among the gut organoids generated directly from intestinal tissues or pluripotent stem cells.
[src:organoids/organoid] Intestinal organoids have also been generated from intestinal stem cells, extracted from adult tissue and cultured in 3D media.
[src:organoids/organoid] These adult stem cell-derived organoids are often referred to as enteroids or colonoids, depending on their segment of origin, and have been established from both the human and murine intestine.
[src:organoids/organoid] Intestinal organoids consist of a single layer of polarized intestinal epithelial cells surrounding a central lumen.
[src:organoids/organoid] As such, recapitulate the crypt-villus structure of the intestine, by recapitulating its function, physiology and organization, and maintaining all the cell types found normally in the structure including intestinal stem cells.
[src:organoids/organoid] Thus, intestinal organoids are a valuable model to study intestinal nutrient transport, drug absorption and delivery, nanomaterials and nanomedicine, incretin hormone secretion, and infection by various enteropathogens.
[src:organoids/organoid] Or recently, Sakib, S., and Zou, S. developed graphene oxide nanoparticles for delivering siRNA regulating expression of tumor necrosis factor-α, that aimed to treat intestinal organoids exhibiting an inflammatory phenotype.
[src:organoids/organoid] Intestinal organoids also recapitulate the crypt-Villus structure to such a high degree of fidelity that they have been successfully transplanted to mouse intestines, and are hence highly regarded as a valuable model for research.
[src:organoids/organoid] One of the fields of research that intestinal organoids have been utilized is that of stem cell niche.
[src:organoids/organoid] In the field of infection biology, different intestinal organoid-based model systems have been explored.
[src:organoids/organoid] On one hand, organoids can be infected in bulk by simply mixing them with the enteropathogen of interest.
[src:organoids/organoid] However, to model infection via a more natural route starting from the intestinal lumen, microinjection of the pathogen is required.
[src:organoids/organoid] In addition, the polarity of intestinal organoids can be inverted, and they can even be dissociated into single cells and cultured as 2D monolayers in order to make both the apical and basolateral sides of the epithelium more easily accessible.
[src:organoids/organoid] Intestinal organoids have also demonstrated therapeutic potential.
[src:organoids/organoid] In order to more accurately recapitulate the intestine in vivo, co-cultures of intestinal organoids and immune cells have been developed.
[src:organoids/organoid] Furthermore, organ-on-a-chip models combine intestinal organoids with other cell types such as endothelial or immune cells as well as peristaltic flow.
[src:organoids/organoid] Gastric organoids recapitulate at least partly the physiology of the stomach.
[src:organoids/organoid] Gastric organoids have been generated directly from pluripotent stem cells through the temporal manipulation of the FGF, WNT, BMP, retinoic acid and EGF signalling pathways in three-dimensional culture conditions.
[src:organoids/organoid] Gastric organoids have also been generated using LGR5 expressing stomach adult stem cells.
[src:organoids/organoid] Gastric organoids have been used as model for the study of cancer along with human disease and development.
[src:organoids/organoid] For example, one study investigated the underlying genetic alterations behind a patient's metastatic tumor population, and identified that unlike the patient's primary tumor, the metastasis had both alleles of the TGFBR2 gene mutated.
[src:organoids/organoid] To further assess the role of TGFBR2 in the metastasis, the investigators created organoids where TGFBR2 expression is knocked down, through which they were able to demonstrate that reduced TGFBR2 activity leads to invasion and metastasis of cancerous tumors both *in vitro* and *in vivo*.
[src:organoids/organoid] Liver progenitor cells, expressing both bile duct and hepatocyte markers, have been known to form organoids in 3D culture conditions with Matrigel and become fully functioning hepatocytes when placed in diseased mouse livers.
[src:organoids/organoid] Later studies demonstrated that similar bipotent progenitor cells derived from adult human bile ducts can be multiplied and maintained long-term in the laboratory; and both human and mouse hepatocytes successfully formed 3D organoid cultures which integrated efficiently into living tissue.
[src:organoids/organoid] Alternatively, it has been shown that if human PSCs are differentiated into hepatic endodermal cells in a 2D culture together with human mesenchymal stem cells and human endothelial cells, when placed in Matrigel they spontaneously form clusters with their own blood vessel networks.
[src:organoids/organoid] When transplanted into in-vivo environments, these clusters can integrate and form functional liver tissue.
[src:organoids/organoid] Lingual organoids are organoids that recapitulate, at least partly, aspects of the tongue physiology.
[src:organoids/organoid] Epithelial lingual organoids have been generated using BMI1 expressing epithelial stem cells in three-dimensional culture conditions through the manipulation of EGF, WNT, and TGF-β.
[src:organoids/organoid] This organoid culture, however, lacks taste receptors, as these cells do not arise from Bmi1 expressing epithelial stem cells.
[src:organoids/organoid] Lingual taste bud organoids containing taste cells, however, have been created using the LGR5+ or CD44+ stem/progenitor cells of circumvallate (CV) papilla tissue.
[src:organoids/organoid] These taste bud organoids have been successfully created both directly from isolated Lgr5- or LGR6-expressing taste stem/progenitor cells. and indirectly, through the isolation, digestion, and subsequent culturing of CV tissue containing Lgr5+ or CD44+ stem/progenitor cells.
[src:organoids/organoid] Cerebellar organoid or hind brain organoids tend to recapitulate the cellular diversity of the fetal cerebellum along with some of its distinct cytoarchitectural features.
[src:organoids/organoid] The generation of cerebellar tissue from PSCs requires a secondary induction which leads to the formation of isthmic organizer, which first appears in the cell aggregate in 3D culture.
[src:organoids/organoid] Over the years this area of research has led to cerebellar organoid development which involves the patterning of human pluripotent stem cells resulting in the generation of both cerebellar excitatory and inhibitory progenitor populations.
[src:organoids/organoid] This includes the rhombic lip and the ventricular zone progenitors.
[src:organoids/organoid] Although further research is still ongoing in context of functional and morphological development of Purkinje cells over a longer period of developmental time.
[src:organoids/organoid] Cancer organoids are three-dimensional in-vitro cell culture systems that are models for studying tumor biology and how different therapeutic react.
[src:organoids/organoid] Derived from stem cells or primary tissue specimens, these structures self-assemble to replicate the architectural and functional characteristics of their tissue of origin.
[src:organoids/organoid] In contrast to traditional two-dimensional monolayer cultures, which inadequately represent the spatial organization and cellular interactions present in tumors, organoids preserve the tumor microenvironment, genomic profiles, and molecular signatures of primary malignancies.
[src:organoids/organoid] Multiple methodologies exist for generating tumor organoids, ranging from simple techniques utilizing non-adhesive culture surfaces to advanced bioengineering approaches that incorporate microfluidic platforms, synthetic biomaterials, and precisely controlled microenvironmental conditions.
[src:organoids/organoid] which is a lymphoid organ where T cells mature.
[src:organoids/organoid] Thymic organoids have been generated through the seeding of thymic stromal cells in 3-dimensional culture.
[src:organoids/organoid] Recent advances in cell repellent microtiter plates has allowed rapid, cost-effective screening of large small molecule drug like libraries against 3D models of pancreas cancer.
[src:organoids/organoid] These models are consistent in phenotype and expression profiles with those found in the lab of Dr.
[src:organoids/organoid] Organoids enable to study how cells interact together in an organ, their interaction with their environment, how diseases affect them and the effect of drugs.
[src:organoids/organoid] *In vitro* culture makes this system easy to manipulate and facilitates their monitoring.
[src:organoids/organoid] While organs are difficult to culture because their size limits the penetration of nutrients, the small size of organoids limits this problem.
[src:organoids/organoid] On the other hand, they do not exhibit all organ features and interactions with other organs are not recapitulated *in vitro*.
[src:organoids/organoid] While research on stem cells and regulation of stemness was the first field of application of intestinal organoids, they are now also used to study e.g. uptake of nutrients, drug transport and secretion of incretin hormones.
[src:organoids/organoid] This is of great relevance in the context of malabsorption diseases as well as metabolic diseases such as obesity, insulin resistance, and diabetes.
[src:organoids/organoid] Organoids provide an opportunity to create cellular models of human disease, which can be studied in the laboratory to better understand the causes of disease and identify possible treatments.
[src:organoids/organoid] The power of organoids in this regard was first shown for a genetic form of microcephaly, where patient cells were used to make cerebral organoids, which were smaller and showed abnormalities in early generation of neurons.
[src:organoids/organoid] In another example, the genome editing system called CRISPR was applied to human pluripotent stem cells to introduce targeted mutations in genes relevant to two different kidney diseases, polycystic kidney disease and focal segmental glomerulosclerosis.
[src:organoids/organoid] These CRISPR-modified pluripotent stem cells were subsequently grown into human kidney organoids, which exhibited disease-specific phenotypes.
[src:organoids/organoid] Kidney organoids from stem cells with polycystic kidney disease mutations formed large, translucent cyst structures from kidney tubules.
[src:organoids/organoid] When cultured in the absence of adherent cues (in suspension), these cysts reached sizes of 1 cm in diameter over several months.
[src:organoids/organoid] Kidney organoids with mutations in a gene linked to focal segmental glomerulosclerosis developed junctional defects between podocytes, the filtering cells affected in that disease.
[src:organoids/organoid] Importantly, these disease phenotypes were absent in control organoids of identical genetic background, but lacking the CRISPR mutations.
[src:organoids/organoid] Comparison of these organoid phenotypes to diseased tissues from mice and humans suggested similarities to defects in early development.
[src:organoids/organoid] As first developed by Takahashi and Yamanaka in 2007, induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSC) can also be reprogrammed from patient skin fibroblasts.
[src:organoids/organoid] These stem cells carry the exact genetic background of the patient including any genetic mutations which might contribute to the development of human disease.
[src:organoids/organoid] Differentiation of these cells into kidney organoids has been performed from patients with Lowe Syndrome due to *ORCL1* mutations.
[src:organoids/organoid] This report compared kidney organoids differentiated from patient iPSC to unrelated control iPSC and demonstrated an inability of patient kidney cells to mobilise transcription factor SIX2 from the golgi complex.
[src:organoids/organoid] A 2013 study by Vosough *et al.* reported a scalable stirred-suspension bioreactor method for generating functional hepatocyte-like cells from human pluripotent stem cells.
[src:organoids/organoid] The derived cells exhibited key hepatic functions *in vitro* and successfully engrafted in mouse models of acute liver injury, improving survival without tumor formation.
[src:organoids/organoid] Other studies have used CRISPR gene editing to correct the patient's mutation in the patient iPSC cells to create an isogenic control, which can be performed simultaneously with iPSC reprogramming.
[src:organoids/organoid] Comparison of a patient iPSC derived organoid against an isogenic control is the current gold standard in the field as it permits isolation of the mutation of interest as the only variable within the experimental model.
[src:organoids/organoid] In one such report, kidney organoids derived from iPSC of a patient with Mainzer-Saldino Syndrome due to compound heterozygous mutations in *IFT140* were compared to an isogenic control organoid in which an *IFT140* variant giving rise to a non-viable mRNA transcript was corrected by CRISPR.
[src:organoids/organoid] Patient kidney organoids demonstrated abnormal ciliary morphology consistent with existing animal models which was rescued to wild type morphology in the gene corrected organoids.
[src:organoids/organoid] Another report utilising an isogenic control demonstrated abnormal nephrin localisation in the glomeruli of kidney organoids generated from a patient with congenital nephrotic syndrome.
[src:organoids/organoid] Things such as epithelial metabolism can also be modelled.
[src:organoids/organoid] Intestinal organoids grown from rectal biopsies using culture protocols established by the Clevers group have been used to model cystic fibrosis, and led to the first application of organoids for personalised treatment.
[src:organoids/organoid] Cystic fibrosis is an inherited disease that is caused by gene mutations of the cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator gene that encodes an epithelial ion channel necessary for healthy epithelial surface fluids.
[src:organoids/organoid] Whereas organoids from non-cystic fibrosis subjects swell in response to forskolin as a consequence of fluid transport into the organoids' lumens, this is severely reduced or absent in organoids derived from people with cystic fibrosis.
[src:organoids/organoid] Swelling could be restored by therapeutics that repair the CFTR protein (CFTR modulators), indicating that individual responses to CFTR modulating therapy could be quantitated in a preclinical laboratory setting.
[src:organoids/organoid] Schwank et al. also demonstrated that the intestinal cystic fibrosis organoid phenotype could be repaired by CRISPR-Cas9 gene editing in 2013.
[src:organoids/organoid] In addition, the authors demonstrated that CFTR modulator responses in intestinal organoids with specific CFTR mutations correlated with published clinical trial data of these treatments.
[src:organoids/organoid] This led to preclinical studies where organoids from patients with extremely rare CFTR mutations for who no treatment was registered were found to respond strongly to a clinically available CFTR modulator.
[src:organoids/organoid] These studies show for the first time that organoids can be used for the individual tailoring of therapy or personalised medicine.
[src:organoids/organoid] The self-renewal and regenerative properties of intestinal organoids make them promising candidates for transplantation therapies, particularly for disease involving epithelial barrier disruption.
[src:organoids/organoid] Notably, transplantation of organoids into the duodenum of mice has been shown to aid in the recovery of mucosal damages on mice with ischemia-reperfusion injury.
[src:organoids/organoid] The first successful transplantation of an organoid into a human, a patient with ulcerative colitis whose cells were used for the organoid, was carried out in 2022.
[src:organoids/organoid] Organoids offer researchers an exceptional model to study developmental biology.
[src:organoids/organoid] Since the identification of pluripotent stem cells, there have been great advancements in directing pluripotent stem cells fate *in vitro* using 2D cultures.
[src:organoids/organoid] These advancements in PSC fate direction, coupled with the advancements in 3D culturing techniques allowed for the creation of organoids that recapitulate the properties of various specific subregions of a multitude of organs.
[src:organoids/organoid] The use of these organoids has thus greatly contributed to expanding our understanding of the processes of organogenesis, and the field of developmental biology.
[src:organoids/organoid] In central nervous system development, for example, organoids have contributed to our understanding of the physical forces that underlie retinal cup formation.
[src:organoids/organoid] More recent work has extended cortical organoid growth periods extensively and at nearly a year under specific differentiation conditions, the organoids persist and have some features of human fetal development stages.
[src:organoids/spheroid] A **spheroid**, also known as an **ellipsoid of revolution** or **rotational ellipsoid**, is a quadric surface obtained by rotating an ellipse about one of its principal axes; in other words, an ellipsoid with two equal semi-diameters.
[src:organoids/spheroid] If the ellipse is rotated about its major axis, the result is a **prolate spheroid**, elongated like a rugby ball.
[src:organoids/spheroid] The American football is similar but has a pointier end than a spheroid could.
[src:organoids/spheroid] If the ellipse is rotated about its minor axis, the result is an **oblate spheroid**, flattened like a lentil or a plain M&M.
[src:organoids/spheroid] If the generating ellipse is a circle, the result is a sphere.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Due to the combined effects of gravity and rotation, the figure of the Earth (and of all planets) is not quite a sphere, but instead is slightly flattened in the direction of its axis of rotation.
[src:organoids/spheroid] For that reason, in cartography and geodesy the Earth is often approximated by an oblate spheroid, known as the reference ellipsoid, instead of a sphere.
[src:organoids/spheroid] The current World Geodetic System model uses a spheroid whose radius is 6,378.137 km (3,963.191 mi) at the Equator and 6,356.752 km (3,949.903 mi) at the poles.
[src:organoids/spheroid] The semi-axis a is the equatorial radius of the spheroid, and c is the distance from centre to pole along the symmetry axis.
[src:organoids/spheroid] The case of *a* = *c* reduces to a sphere.
[src:organoids/spheroid] where $e_{p}^{2}=1-{\frac {a^{2}}{c^{2}}}.$ In both cases, eo and ep may be identified as the eccentricity (see ellipse).
[src:organoids/spheroid] These formulas are identical in the sense that the formula for *S*o can be used to calculate the surface area of a prolate spheroid and vice versa.
[src:organoids/spheroid] However, eo then becomes imaginary and can no longer directly be identified with the eccentricity.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Both of these results may be cast into many other forms using standard mathematical identities and relations between parameters of the ellipse.
[src:organoids/spheroid] where β is the *reduced latitude* or *parametric latitude* and λ is the longitude, with domain −⁠π/2⁠ < *β* < +⁠π/2⁠ and −π < *λ* < +π, respectively.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Both of these curvatures are a function of latitude only and are always positive, so that every point on a spheroid is elliptic.
[src:organoids/spheroid] The first *eccentricity* (usually simply eccentricity, as above) is often used instead of flattening.
[src:organoids/spheroid] All modern geodetic ellipsoids are defined by the semi-major axis plus either the semi-minor axis (giving the aspect ratio), the flattening, or the first eccentricity.
[src:organoids/spheroid] While these definitions are mathematically interchangeable, real-world calculations must lose some precision.
[src:organoids/spheroid] To avoid confusion, an ellipsoidal definition considers its own values to be exact in the form it gives.
[src:organoids/spheroid] The most common shapes for the density distribution of protons and neutrons in an atomic nucleus are spherical, prolate, and oblate spheroidal, where the polar axis is assumed to be the spin axis (or direction of the spin angular momentum vector).
[src:organoids/spheroid] Deformed nuclear shapes occur as a result of the competition between electromagnetic repulsion between protons, surface tension and quantum shell effects.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Spheroids are common in 3D cell cultures.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Rotating equilibrium spheroids include the Maclaurin spheroid and the Jacobi ellipsoid.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Spheroid is also a shape of archaeological artifacts.
[src:organoids/spheroid] The oblate spheroid is the approximate shape of rotating planets and other celestial bodies, including Earth, Saturn, Jupiter, and the quickly spinning star Altair.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Saturn is the most oblate planet in the Solar System, with a flattening of 0.09796.
[src:organoids/spheroid] See planetary flattening and equatorial bulge for details.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Enlightenment scientist Isaac Newton, working from Jean Richer's pendulum experiments and Christiaan Huygens's theories for their interpretation, reasoned that Jupiter and Earth are oblate spheroids owing to their centrifugal force.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Earth's diverse cartographic and geodetic systems are based on reference ellipsoids, all of which are oblate.
[src:organoids/spheroid] The prolate spheroid is the approximate shape of the ball used in American football and in rugby.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Several moons of the Solar System approximate prolate spheroids in shape, though they are closer to triaxial ellipsoids.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Examples are Saturn's satellites Mimas, Enceladus, and Tethys and Uranus's satellite Miranda.
[src:organoids/spheroid] In contrast to being distorted into oblate spheroids via rapid rotation, celestial objects distort slightly into prolate spheroids via tidal forces when they orbit a massive body in a close orbit.
[src:organoids/spheroid] The most extreme example is Jupiter's moon Io, which becomes slightly more or less prolate in its orbit due to a slight eccentricity, causing intense volcanism.
[src:organoids/spheroid] The major axis of the prolate spheroid does not run through the satellite's poles in this case, but through the two points on its equator directly facing toward and away from the primary.
[src:organoids/spheroid] This combines with the smaller oblate distortion from the synchronous rotation to cause the body to become triaxial.
[src:organoids/spheroid] The term is also used to describe the shape of some nebulae such as the Crab Nebula.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Fresnel zones, used to analyze wave propagation and interference in space, are a series of concentric prolate spheroids with principal axes aligned along the direct line-of-sight between a transmitter and a receiver.
[src:organoids/spheroid] The atomic nuclei of the actinide and lanthanide elements are shaped like prolate spheroids.
[src:organoids/spheroid] In anatomy, near-spheroid organs such as testis may be measured by their long and short axes.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Many submarines have a shape which can be described as prolate spheroid.
[src:organoids/spheroid] For a spheroid having uniform density, the moment of inertia is that of an ellipsoid with an additional axis of symmetry.
[src:organoids/spheroid] Given a description of a spheroid as having a major axis c, and minor axes a = b, the moments of inertia along these principal axes are C, A, and B.
[src:organoids/spheroid] However, in a spheroid the minor axes are symmetrical.
